"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443473","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-18","<p>The Ministry of Justice welcomes the work done by the Low Commission in producing its reports, and notes its recommendation on Alternative Dispute Resolution. As part of our work to reform the courts we are considering how to make processes speedier and more accessible.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-01-18T17:47:51.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443473/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443473/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-08","Civil Law: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the second bullet point of page 26 of the report, entitled Getting it right in social welfare law, published by the Low Commission in March 2015, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of the Commission's recommendation.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443474","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-18","<p>The Ministry of Justice welcomes the work done by the Low Commission in producing its reports and recommendations, and we recognise the importance of advice being available in all contexts.</p><p>As the Justice Secretary said in June, we want to create a one nation justice system, and we are considering how this can be taken forward.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-01-18T16:24:51.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443474/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443474/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-08","Civil Law: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the feasibility of the recommendation of the Low Commission to establish a national advice and legal support fund funded through annual contributions from his Department, the Cabinet Office, the Big Lottery Fund and the Department for Work and Pensions.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443476","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>Following a successful pilot, the practice in the Social Security and Child Support Tribunal has been for judges to provide a brief summary of reasons for their decision. This is helping the Department for Work and Pensions with decision making. In the Immigration and Asylum Chamber, and in other tribunals, judges routinely give full written reasons for their decisions and Ministry of Justice officials regularly meet with colleagues from the Home Office and other government departments to discuss any underlying reasons that may be contributing to high overturn rates.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-01-15T11:23:36.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443476/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443476/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-08","Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department has taken to develop protocols with (a) the Department for Work and Pensions, (b) the Home Office and (c) other government departments and agencies to improve the quality of decision making to reduce the number of assessments overturned on appeal.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443478","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>During the talks last autumn, significant progress was made on how to implement the legacy bodies set out in the Stormont House Agreement. It was regrettable that agreement on all the legacy issues could not be reached during the talks process. I have, however, commenced a round of engagement with victims and others as we seek to achieve the consensus needed to bring forward legislation to address the outstanding legacy issues.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-13T15:39:10.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443478/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443478/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-08","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent progress has been made on the remaining legacy issues in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","21611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443479","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>I recently met the Commissioner for Victims and Survivors and the Victims and Survivors Forum and I have commenced a round of engagement with the political parties. I will continue to meet with victims and others as we seek to achieve the consensus needed to bring forward legislation to address the outstanding legacy issues.</p><br />","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-13T15:40:36.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443479/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443479/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-08","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when she plans to commence talks on the remaining legacy issues in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","21612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443480","Prime Minister","false","2016-01-15","<p>Transparency will be a vital part of the Anti-Corruption Summit we will host in London in May. We continue to lead the way on company transparency, and we continue to push this agenda with the Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies, as well as our other international partners.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2016-01-15T12:32:46.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443480/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443480/answer",,,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-01-08","British Overseas Territories: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether he plans that company ownership transparency in the UK's Overseas Territories with financial centres be on the agenda for the forthcoming Anti-Corruption Summit.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","21654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443481","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-18","<p>Spending Review 2015 set out a long-term budget of £55.7bn (2015 prices) for delivering HS2. Of this, approximately £27.2bn has been apportioned to Phase One and £28.5bn to Phase Two.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-18T10:34:56.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443481/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443481/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 11.10 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, how the £55 billion budget for High Speed 2 has been split between phase 1 and phase 2 of that project.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443482","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-13","<p><strong>Part A</strong></p><p>Within HS2 Ltd, 4 staff have gone through a disciplinary process since March 2013. Only one of these cases has proceeded to an Employment Tribunal. There are no central records prior to this date.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong>Part B</strong></p><p>Within the Department for Transport (excluding its Agencies), there have been 49 disciplinary cases and 12 Employment Tribunals since April 2013. Information prior to this date is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-13T14:07:45.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443482/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443482/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff at HS2 Ltd and his Department have gone through or are going through disciplinary or employment tribunal process since HS2 Ltd was formed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443483","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-13","<p><strong>Part A</strong></p><p>HS2 Ltd do not have any staff who have been re-engaged on a self-employed or consultancy basis.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong>Part B</strong></p><p>The Department for Transport (excluding its Agencies) has 3 staff that have been re engaged on a self-employed or consultancy basis during this time period.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-13T13:53:39.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443483/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443483/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many members of staff have left HS2 Ltd or his Department and been re-engaged on a self-employed or consultancy basis by either organisation in each year since the formation of HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443484","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-13","<p>HS2 Ltd do not hold a record of organisations from which employees are hired. However, there are 3 staff known to HS2 Ltd that have transferred during the last two years from Department for Transport, one from the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills and one from the Cabinet Office.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-13T13:57:55.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443484/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443484/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff have transferred from another government department to HS2 Ltd in each year since HS2 Ltd was formed; and from what Departments those staff transferred.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443485","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-13","<p>The table below sets out the number of personnel by grade employed by or on secondment to HS2 Ltd who have left the organisation in each year since 2013.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>HS2 Grade</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Civil Service/DfT Grade</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>22+</p></td><td><p>SCS2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>SCS1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>SCS1</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>G6</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>G6</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>G7</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>SEO</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>SEO</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>HEO</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>HEO</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>EO</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>AO</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>AO</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>AA</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>81</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-13T14:11:41.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443485/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443485/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many personnel employed by or on secondment to HS2 Ltd of each grade have left the organisation in each year since it was formed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443486","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-18","<p>In December 2015 the Federation of Petroleum Suppliers sent the Department for Transport an application for the UK to submit a request to the European Commission, under Article 14(1) of Regulation (EC) 561/2006, for a derogation on the weekly rest requirement in the EU drivers’ hours rules for drivers of tankers delivering domestic fuel. This application is being considered and a decision on whether to support it and apply to the Commission will be made in due course.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-18T10:45:20.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443486/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443486/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will support a claim by (a) petroleum suppliers who supply home heating oil and (b) other petroleum suppliers for a derogation from the EU rules on the amount of weekly rest required by such suppliers' drivers; and what stage that application for a derogation has reached.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","21606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443487","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-18","<p>The current estimate for High Speed 2 rolling stock is approximately £7.0bn (in 2015 prices).</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-18T10:41:51.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443487/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443487/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department currently uses for the cost of rolling stock for High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443488","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-18","<p>The £55.7bn long-term funding envelope for delivering HS2 includes funding provision for rolling stock.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-18T10:22:05.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443488/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443488/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to paragraph 11.10 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, whether the figure of £55.7 billion for High Speed 2 is exclusive of the cost of rolling stock for that project.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443489","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-18","<p>In the 2015 Spending Review, the Government restated the long-term funding envelope for the HS2 programme at £55.7bn in 2015 prices. This envelope includes funding for Phase Two with contingency. We intend to deliver the most cost effective design for HS2 and ensure that the best value is achieved. We have a regime in place for delivering HS2 and managing costs which will ensure there is sufficient funding for community and environmental mitigation.</p><br /><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-18T12:57:47.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443489/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443489/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-08","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department plans to take to ensure that communities and environmental mitigation is allocated sufficient funding in Phase 2 of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","21655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443490","Wales Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>There are currently 23 women and 23 men working at the Wales Office.</p>","Preseli Pembrokeshire","Stephen Crabb",,"2016-01-13T16:17:31.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443490/answer","Biography information for Stephen Crabb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443490/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-01-08","Wales Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many people of each gender work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443491","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-18","<p>The Department carefully considers all relevant publications.</p><br /><p>The number of people in in-work relative low income is 200,000 lower than at its peak in 2008/09. Moreover, Universal Credit, our investment in childcare, the National Living Wage, and our increase in the personal tax allowance will support individuals and working households by enabling them to earn more and keep more of what they earn.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-18T17:15:46.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443491/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443491/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-08","Low Incomes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the implications for his polices of the conclusion of the Joseph Rowntree Foundation report, entitled Monitoring Poverty and Social Exclusion 2015, that the number of people in low-income working households has risen from 5.2 million to 6.7 million in the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","21621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443492","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-18","<p>The Department carefully considers all relevant publications.</p><br /><p>The Prime Minister recently announced that the Government is bringing forward a ‘help to save’ scheme to encourage those on low incomes to build up a rainy day fund. The Government has also taken significant steps to support the credit union movement to help people to save and access responsible credit.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-18T17:22:37.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443492/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443492/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-08","Cost of Living","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the implications for his polices of the conclusion of the Joseph Rowntree Foundation report, entitled Monitoring Poverty and Social Exclusion 2015, that the proportion of families in the bottom fifth of income distribution with no savings rose to 69 per cent over the last 10 years partly due to the rising cost of living","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","21623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443493","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-18","<p>The Department carefully considers all relevant publications.</p><br /><p>We know that work is the best route out of poverty and that is why we are reforming welfare and cutting taxes to make sure work always pays and people get to keep more of what they earn. The annual average income of the poorest fifth of households has risen in real terms, compared to 2007/08. Looking forward, working families can expect to see their earnings increase, with average earnings growth expected to reach around 4% a year by 2020, while the current OBR forecast is for inflation to remain relatively low over the next two years.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-18T17:31:13.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443493/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443493/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-08","Cost of Living","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the implications for his polices of the conclusion of the Joseph Rowntree Foundation report, entitled Monitoring Poverty and Social Exclusion 2015, that people in the bottom fifth of income distribution saw their living costs increase faster than average because they spent more money on essential goods.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","21624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443494","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>Universal Credit is paid on the basis of earnings. Information on types of contracts that claimants are on is not routinely collected.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-13T16:42:17.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443494/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443494/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-08","Universal Credit: Zero Hours Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what information his Department holds on the number of universal credit claimants who are employed on a zero-hours contract.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","21673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443164","Attorney General","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) has issued guidance to strengthen prosecutions in support of the introduction of the Modern Slavery Act 2015. The CPS continues to deliver joint training with the police. The increased awareness and emphasis on working with the police to build stronger cases should lead to an improvement in the number of successful prosecutions.</p><br /><p>The Director of Public Prosecutionsis hosting a summit with the Heads of the Prosecution Services in the UK and the Lord Advocate for Scotland in February 2016 to launch joint commitments to provide a more robust UK response to human trafficking and slavery.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-01-13T13:39:36.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443164/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443164/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-01-07","Human Trafficking: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps the Crown Prosecution Service is taking to improve the number of successful prosecutions for human trafficking offences.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","21543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443165","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<br /><p>As announced in the 2015 Spending Review, in order to prioritise funding to allow the core adult skills participation budgets to be protected in cash terms, savings are being made from the supporting budgets including the UK Commission for Employment and Skills (UKCES).</p><br /><p>Whitehall Departments will be withdrawing their funding for UKCES during the 2016-17 financial year. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills is working with UKCES to manage the implications of this decision.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-12T16:34:10.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443165/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443165/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-07","UK Commission for Employment and Skills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what his plans are for the future of the UK Commission for Employment and Skills.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","21583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443166","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-22","<p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) has not had any direct employees in Stoke-on-Trent since before 2010.</p><br /><p>I have asked Chief Executives of the Executive Agencies to respond directly to the Hon Member and these are attached. This information is not held by BIS in respect of non-Departmental Public Bodies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-01-22T14:39:09.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443166/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443166/answer","Ordinary Written PQ 21440 Executive Agency replies (00411).pdf","Ordinary Written PQ 21440 Executive Agency replies (00411).pdf","Executive Agency replies","Executive Agency replies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443166/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-07","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443167","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-25","<p>The apprenticeship levy will apply to both the private and public sectors. We understand that employers in sectors where a levy is already in place will want clarity on what the introduction of an apprenticeships levy means for them. We will publish further details in due course.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-25T11:23:50.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443167/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443167/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-07","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how the Government plans to adapt implementation of the apprenticeships levy for different sectors.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","21438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443168","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<br /><p>The current apprenticeships funding mechanism is being reformed to deliver a high-quality, employer-led system. In the transition period, we will be continuing to use the current system (which has delivered strong apprenticeships growth) and work with employers to help them take on apprentices. We will monitor take-up prior to the levy introduction.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-12T16:32:09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443168/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443168/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-07","Apprentices: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the risk of employers waiting until the new digital voucher funding mechanism is in place before taking on new apprentices.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","21461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443169","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-15","<p>No jobs in my Department or in each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 or plan to be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-01-15T12:02:27.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443169/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443169/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-07","Cabinet Office: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443170","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-01-12T11:12:15.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443170/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443170/answer","21531 FINAL.pdf","21531 FINAL.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Full-Time Employment","UKSA Letter to Member - Full-Time Employment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443170/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-01-07","Employment: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) jobs and (b) residents in full-time employment there were in the London Borough of Newham in each year from 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443171","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Financial Services Compensation Scheme regularly publishes details of the interventions it has undertaken to protect depositors. The Scheme announced that it had protected the savings of members in five credit unions which entered default in 2014; and six in 2015.</p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-12T15:20:34.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443171/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443171/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Credit Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many credit unions were subject to intervention by the Financial Services Compensation Scheme in 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","21538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443172","HM Treasury","false","2016-05-11","<p>Since its introduction in 1996, the Landfill Communities Fund (LCF) has contributed over £1.4bn to community projects in areas affected by a local landfill site and the government acknowledges the positive impact of this funding for communities. However, as the LCF is a tax credit scheme, it reduces tax revenues and we therefore have a responsibility to seek value for money for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>Despite difficult decisions on spending, the government has decided to retain and reform the LCF. Following representations on the issue of contributing third parties, the government softened proposals in this area at Budget 2016, and the requirement for a 10% landfill operator contribution has not been set in legislation. However, the government wants landfill operators to make a greater contribution to the LCF, and the regulator of the scheme, ENTRUST, has published guidance setting out this expectation.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-05-11T09:12:27.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443172/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443172/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Landfill Communities Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from (a) landfill operators and (b) environmental bodies on the proposed removal of third party contributions from the Landfill Communities Fund; and whether he plans to change that proposal in response to those representations.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","21539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443173","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-08","<p>A decision on funding allocations for the Illegal Money Lending teams will be taken shortly.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-08T15:24:05.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443173/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443173/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-07","Money Lenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much funding has been allocated to the Illegal Money Lending Units over the next three years.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","21492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443174","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","<p>The economy forecast produced by the OBR reflects current Government policy. As laid out in the Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011, ‘Where any Government policies are relevant to the performance of that duty, the Office - must have regard to those policies, but may not consider what the effect of any alternative policies would be.’ The OBR note as risks to the fiscal forecast any significant policy commitments that are not quantifiable.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-12T15:30:37.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443174/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443174/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Economic Growth","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 19047, what discussions he has had with the Office for Budget Responsibility on including the potential effect of recent Conservative Party manifesto commitments in its forecasting of economic growth.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443175","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-14","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-giftsand-overseas-travel The lead department for this measure, the Department for Work and Pensions, has regular meetings with relevant organisations and will meet with them to discuss how the application of local housing allowance rates to social sector tenants, including those living in supported housing, will work as the policy is developed.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-14T17:02:29.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443175/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443175/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what organisations he has met to discuss the introduction of the capping of housing benefit for tenants in supported housing at the local rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443176","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","The use of standard email is insecure and therefore in order to protect customers’ information, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not use it when dealing with sensitive personal and financial information. However, HMRC does answer MPs enquiries electronically in cases where the response does not include any sensitive customer data.","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-12T17:28:43.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443176/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443176/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he is taking steps to enable his Department's child tax credit department to answer the enquiries of hon. Members electronically.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","21582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443177","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is an independent regulator. Treasury Ministers had no discussions with the chairman before the FCA announced the decision to discontinue the review of banking culture included in the 2015-16 Business Plan. The FCA has set out in its published response to a Freedom of Information request, the dates when it communicated its decision to discontinue this review to other organisations. This response is available on the FCA website.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-14T16:34:06.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443177/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443177/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the chairman of the Financial Conduct Authority on that body's decision not to undertake its planned review of banking culture.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443178","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is actively targeting operational and intelligence activity, as well as a range of other options, to tackle this issue. The work is ongoing and therefore the information requested is only available at disproportionate cost. As part of the approach to tackling this particular type of tax evasion HMRC launched the e-marketplace campaign, the results of which are available on gov.uk.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-12T17:26:18.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443178/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443178/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Electronic Commerce: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 26 November 2015 to Question 17211, how much revenue has been recovered by actively targeting operational and intelligence activity to tackle the issues of online VAT fraud in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443179","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","<p>We do not hold information on the number of faxes received on child tax credits within HMRC.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-12T14:37:02.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443179/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443179/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Child Tax Credit: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much correspondence the child tax credits enquiry department receives by fax each day.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","21596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443180","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-18","<p>No jobs within HM Treasury, Office for Budget Responsibility , Government Internal Audit Agency, Debt Management Office and Government Actuaries Department have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and there are currently no plans for any to be abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.</p><br /><p>As announced in November 2015, HM Revenue and Customs plans to close Blackburn House in Stoke-on-Trent in 2019/20. The 256 posts currently in Stoke will transfer to new regional centres and the Department has committed to working with its staff to ensure that as many of those who do want to continue working for HMRC will be able to do so.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-18T11:48:22.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443180/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443180/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Treasury: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443181","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","<p>Treasury Group – Bodies can be found in the published Report and Accounts. The latest Annual Report and accounts for 2014-15 is published on line and can be viewed in the link below:-</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hm-treasury-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hm-treasury-annual-report-and-accounts-2014-to-2015</a></p><br />","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-12T15:26:32.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443181/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443181/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Treasury","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will provide a list of all the departments within HM Treasury.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443182","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-15","<p>According to the National Trading Standards Annual report 2014/15, the England and Wales illegal money lending teams commenced 365 operations into 756 suspected money lenders in 2014/15.</p><br /><p>In the same period 42 individuals were charged or had proceedings instituted against them for illegal money lending in England and Wales. Trading Standards Scotland referred a further 9 individuals to the Procurator Fiscal for illegal money lending in 2014/15.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-15T14:45:28.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443182/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443182/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-07","Money Lenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many illegal money lenders Illegal Money Lending Units prevented from operating in 2015.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","21493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443183","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed the regulation of the debt management market, transferring regulatory responsibility from the Office of Fair Trading to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) a more robust and better resourced regulator.</p><br /><p>The FCA is directing the clients of Brightsource Debt Management towards free debt advice and is engaging with the administrator to ensure the interests of clients are protected.</p><br /><p>The FCA require debt management firms which receive client money for the purposes of paying off client debts to pay that money to creditors as soon as is reasonably practical, normally within 5 business days, unless the firm has disclosed to the client that it will hold the money for a longer period in its terms and conditions.</p><br /><p>The FCA supervises the market; it has a broad enforcement toolkit to punish breaches of its rules and there is no limit on the fines it can levy.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-15T13:13:42.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443183/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443183/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what support the Financial Conduct Authority has offered to people affected by the recent administration of Brightsource Debt Management; and what steps his Department is taking to ensure that debt consolidation companies make timely payments to creditors so that their customers' loans are paid down as quickly as possible.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","21495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443184","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","<p>As set out in the Charter for Budget Responsibility, the OBR is required to provide an analysis of the risks surrounding the economic outlook. As a result in every Economic and Fiscal Outlook the OBR sets out the risks and uncertainties surrounding the economic and fiscal forecast. The Treasury does not hold information on the reasons why the Office for Budget Responsibility did not include net migration as one of the key risks or sensitivities to the medium term forecast.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-01-12T15:22:41.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443184/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443184/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Immigration: Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 19017, what information his Department holds on the reasons why the Office for Budget Responsibility does not view changes to net migration as one of the key risks or sensitivities to the medium term forecast.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443185","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-12","The value of the contract was estimated at between £55m and £75m at contract award. Payments to Concentrix are based on the results they deliver, taking into account the quality and accuracy of their work.Concentrix are not paid for any cases where the decision they make is overturned.","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-01-12T17:23:41.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443185/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443185/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-07","Concentrix","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department spent on the outsourcing of its compliance review to Concentrix; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443187","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>A copy of the specification for the review has been put in the Library of the House.</p><p>The Review began in January 2015. The Department of Work and Pensions and the Department for Communities and Local Government commissioned Ipsos MORI in partnership with Imogen Blood and Associates and Housing and Support Partnership Limited to undertake the evidence review. The report will be published later this year.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21572","2016-01-14T17:14:55.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443187/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443187/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2015 to Question 19365, on supported housing, if he will place the remit of the evidence review in the Library.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443188","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-15","<p>It is for local authorities to allocate funding to individual services from their overall budget.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-01-15T13:20:40.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443188/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443188/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Vulnerable Adults: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funding his Department provides for local authorities to discharge their responsibilities for vulnerable adult transport.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443189","Department of Health","false","2016-01-13","<p>When it is determined by a local authority that an adult has eligible care and support needs, and the provision of transport is required to meet the outcomes in the adults care plan, this may be funded as part of a formal social care package.</p><br /><p>As such, the Social Care Precept would be a possible funding stream for the local authority in these instances.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-13T15:26:45.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443189/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443189/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Vulnerable Adults: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is his policy that vulnerable adult transport can be funded through the two per cent Social Care Precept.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443190","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>Ministers from the Department of Communities and Local Government and the Department of Work and Pensions regularly consult with a wide range of organisations as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Ministers and officials from both Departments are meeting relevant organisations from all sectors.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21484 ; 21485","2016-01-14T17:08:33.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443190/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443190/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what consultation his Department has undertaken with councils with statutory responsibility for vulnerable people in supported housing (a) before and (b) since the announcement that housing benefit for tenants in supported housing will be capped at the local rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443191","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Chancellor’s Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 (Cm9162), presented to Parliament on 26 November 2015, makes clear that the two per cent social care precept must be spent entirely on adult social care.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","21290","2016-01-14T17:16:05.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443191/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443191/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans that the two per cent social care precept will be ring-fenced for particular items of expenditure.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443192","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>No jobs in either my Department or each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 or will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-14T16:56:32.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443192/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443192/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Department for Communities and Local Government: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443193","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-12","<p>To help local authorities in Lancashire and their community’s recovery from the impacts of Storms Desmond and Eva, between the 5 December 2015 and 8 January 2016, my Department has provided eligible local authorities in Lancashire with a total of £5,620,652. Further payments will be made in due course where appropriate.</p><p>This funding includes in advance payments in the form of Communities and Business Recovery Scheme, business rate relief and council tax discount payments. Disbursement of this funding will be a matter for local authorities to determine.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-01-12T16:23:09.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443193/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443193/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Floods: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many £500 grants were provided to help households affected by flooding in each district and unitary authority in Lancashire between 5 December 2015 and 7 January 2016; and how much funding has been received by each of those councils to provide such grants up to 7 January 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","21597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443194","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>A copy of the specification for the review has been put in the Library of the House.</p><p>The Review began in January 2015. The Department of Work and Pensions and the Department for Communities and Local Government commissioned Ipsos MORI in partnership with Imogen Blood and Associates and Housing and Support Partnership Limited to undertake the evidence review. The report will be published later this year.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21500","2016-01-14T17:14:55.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443194/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443194/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2015 to Question 19365, on housing benefit, (a) when the evidence review began, (b) who has been commissioned to undertake that review and (c) when he expects that review to be published.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443195","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>Ministers from the Department of Communities and Local Government and the Department of Work and Pensions regularly consult with a wide range of organisations as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Ministers and officials from both Departments are meeting relevant organisations from all sectors.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21483 ; 21485","2016-01-14T17:08:33.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443195/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443195/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what consultation his Department has undertaken with organisations that provide supported housing for vulnerable people (a) before and (b) since the announcement that housing benefit for tenants in supported housing will be capped at the local rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443196","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>Ministers from the Department of Communities and Local Government and the Department of Work and Pensions regularly consult with a wide range of organisations as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Ministers and officials from both Departments are meeting relevant organisations from all sectors.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21483 ; 21484","2016-01-14T17:08:33.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443196/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443196/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what organisations he has met to discuss the introduction of the capping of housing benefit for tenants in supported housing at the local rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21485"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443197","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department of Work and Pensions have jointly commissioned the Supported Accommodation Review to better understand the scale, shape and cost of supported accommodation. The Review will provide more robust and up-to-date information relating to supported housing, including the principal user groups. The Review will report later this year.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21487 ; 21488","2016-01-14T17:06:21.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443197/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443197/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the likely number of (a) new tenants and (b) tenancies in supported housing in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443198","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department of Work and Pensions have jointly commissioned the Supported Accommodation Review to better understand the scale, shape and cost of supported accommodation. The Review will provide more robust and up-to-date information relating to supported housing, including the principal user groups. The Review will report later this year.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21486 ; 21488","2016-01-14T17:06:21.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443198/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443198/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) frail elderly people, (b) young people leaving care, (c) women fleeing domestic violence, (d) people recovering from alcohol and substance misuse, (e) people with mental health issues and (f) people with physical or learning disabilities live in supported housing and are eligible for housing benefit.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443199","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government and the Department of Work and Pensions have jointly commissioned the Supported Accommodation Review to better understand the scale, shape and cost of supported accommodation. The Review will provide more robust and up-to-date information relating to supported housing, including the principal user groups. The Review will report later this year.</p><p><br></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","21486 ; 21487","2016-01-14T17:06:21.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443199/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443199/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Supported Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people who live in supported housing are eligible for housing benefit.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443200","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-26","<p>In 2013-14, an estimated 1.2 million children in England were living in overcrowded accommodation. Estimates for recent years from the English Housing Survey are shown in the attached table.</p><br />","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-26T14:56:31.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443200/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443200/answer","PQ 21533 Table.docx","PQ 21533 Table.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443200/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443200/answer/previousversion/38448","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443200/answer/previousversion/38448",,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Housing: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many children in England have lived in overcrowded homes in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","21533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443201","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Department publishes estimates of the numbers and proportions of homes in the social rented sector that have been classified as overcrowded. The proportion was estimated as 7.3% in 2010/11 and as 6.2% in 2013/14. These figures are from the English Housing Survey and are available at:</p><p>Annex Table 1.13 at: https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/469214/2013-14_Section_1_Households_tables_and_figures_FINAL.xlsx</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-12T16:56:53.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443201/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443201/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Social Rented Housing: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many and what proportion of homes in the social rented sector have been classified as overcrowded in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","21534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443202","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-19","<p>Sport England, which helps local authorities develop and implement Playing Pitch Strategies to protect existing playing fields as well as meet future demand, recommends that the strategy should be updated every three years. In its role as statutory consultee, Sport England also monitors the number of planning applications that have an impact on playing fields and objects where it believes local sports provision could be harmed. As set out in our sports strategy, published last month, this Government is committed to improving the quality of community sports facilities.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-01-19T17:22:16.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443202/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443202/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Playing Fields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, after how long it is his policy to take action when a local planning authority has not produced a playing pitch strategy; and what powers his Department has to taken such action after that period.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","21513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443203","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Ofcom Code of Pratice on Broadband Speeds, effective from October 2015, requires internet service providers (ISPs) to give customers clear and accurate information on home broadband speeds, including the maximum speeds they can achieve, the estimated speed on the customer’s line, and factors that may slow down the speed, such as any fair use or traffic management policies.</p>ISPs must have systems in place to find the cause of speed problems, take steps to fix any issue they are responsible for, and explain to customers if they can do anything to improve the situation. As a result of the October 2015 revised code, customers can terminate contracts at any time without penalty if they receive speeds significantly below the ‘minimum guaranteed access line speed'; previously customers could only terminate within the first three months. <br />","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-15T11:34:55.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443203/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443203/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans he has to bring forward proposals to ensure service level agreement requirements incorporated into broadband supplier contracts with their customers ensure a reasonable minimum speed of download is maintained and commensurate with the advertised product.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","21499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443204","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Responsible Gambling Strategy Board (RGSB), was set up to by the Gambling Commission to advise on priorities for research relating to responsible gambling. Research into gambling related harm is commissioned by the independent charity, the Responsible Gambling Trust (RGT), taking into account the priorities set out by the RGSB. At the request of the RGSB, the RGT is currently commissioning research to define Gambling Related Harm which will consider the wider health impacts of problem gambling. The Government continues to encourage such research.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-01-14T17:06:35.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443204/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443204/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will commission independent research on the effect of fixed-odds betting terminals on the health of their users and on the communities in which they are prevalent.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","21567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443205","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Scotland Bill will give the Scottish Parliament and Scottish Ministers the power to vary the number of sub-category B2 gaming machines (FOBTs) permitted by new betting premises licences. The UK Government will retain the equivalent powers on FOBTs for the rest of the UK, except for Northern Ireland where gambling is a devolved matter.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-01-14T17:04:40.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443205/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443205/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Gaming Machines: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of devolving to the Scottish Parliament all aspects of (a) gaming and betting legislation, (b) including curbing the terminals' speed of play and maximum stakes for fixed-odds betting terminals and (c) other regulation of fixed-odds betting terminals.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","21566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443206","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Department has had no offices in the area in the timeframe.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-15T11:31:29.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443206/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443206/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443207","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-12","<p>Representations have been received from one League One club, Peterborough United, and from Grimsby Town in the National League about the possible introduction of safe standing accommodation at their respective grounds.</p><br /><p>The Minister for Sport has also met Andrew R T Davies, Leader of the Conservative Party at the Welsh Assembly to discuss the possibility of a safe standing pilot in Wales.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2016-01-12T17:08:25.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443207/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443207/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Football: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations his Department has received from professional football teams in England and Wales on the potential introduction of safe-standing facilities at higher tier sports stadia in the last year; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","21466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443208","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-13","<p>Information relating to gender distribution in government departments is collated by the Office for National Statistics and published under the Annual Civil Service Employment Survey each year. The number of each gender working in DCMS is:</p><p /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Gender</p></td><td><p>Headcount</p></td><td><p>%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>220</p></td><td><p>46</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>260</p></td><td><p>54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p> 480 <p><p></td><td></td></tr></tbody></table>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-01-13T16:05:10.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443208/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443208/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-01-07","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many people of each gender work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443209","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-12","<br /><p>The requested information, as at 1 October 2015, is provided below:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>Female</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK Regular Armed Forces</p></td><td><p>136,750</p></td><td><p>15,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Future Reserves 2020 Volunteer Reserve</p></td><td><p>28,740</p></td><td><p>4,540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ministry of Defence core civilian personnel</p></td><td><p>22,140</p></td><td><p>14,970</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Full analyses of UK Armed Forces and Ministry of Defence civilian diversity statistics are published on a regular basis and can be found at the following links:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-biannual-diversity-statistics-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-biannual-diversity-statistics-2015</a></p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-civilian-personnel-quarterly-report-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mod-civilian-personnel-quarterly-report-2015</a></p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-12T17:28:56.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443209/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443209/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Ministry of Defence: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people of each gender work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443210","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>This information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>In April 2010 there were 20 Ministry of Defence (MOD) civilian personnel employed at locations within the Unitary Authority of Stoke-on-Trent; in October 2015 there were 10. All numbers are rounded.</p><p>Full details of how the planned reductions in MOD civilian staff numbers announced in the Strategic Defence and Security Review will be profiled over the next five years are not yet available and will be developed as programmes mature.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-14T16:24:11.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443210/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443210/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Ministry of Defence: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443211","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>Army medicals result in the allocation of a graded &quot;medical deployability standard&quot; reflecting those active roles for which personnel are declared fit. It is not a simple pass or fail. Unlike their regular counterparts, Army Reserve personnel do not undertake annual medical assessments. The only mandatory medicals are during the recruitment process and during mobilisation. The medical care of Reserve personnel lies with their General Practitioners and the National Health Service unless they are mobilised at which point the medical care responsibility transfers to the Defence Medical Services.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-01-14T16:15:34.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443211/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443211/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Royal Regiment of Scotland: Reserve Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) establishment and (b) strength personnel of (i) 6 SCOTS and (ii) 7 SCOTS have failed a medical in each year from 2012 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443212","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Royal Navy has supported one dedicated Search and Rescue operation in the Mediterranean Sea over the past five years, which was Op WEALD in 2015. This constituted the UK's contribution to the international efforts in response to the migrant crisis. The additional cost of the Royal Navy support to this operation was £2.58 million, which was funded through the UK Aid Budget.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-12T17:22:08.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443212/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443212/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Navy: Mediterranean Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of Royal Navy search and rescue operations in the Mediterranean Sea in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","21465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443213","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-12","<p>A joint UN/Syrian Arab Red Crescent/International Committee of the Red Cross operation delivered humanitarian assistance, including food, non-food items, and medical supplies, to Madaya on 11 January. With land access available there are no plans for the RAF to deliver humanitarian assistance by air.</p><br />","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-12T17:23:29.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443213/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443213/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Syria: Food Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will direct the armed forces to drop emergency food aid to the under siege town of Madaya in Syria.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","21436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443214","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>The River Class Offshore Patrol Vessels HMS TYNE and HMS SEVERN and the Survey Vessel HMS ECHO currently provide the Royal Navy's contribution to fishery protection duties within the United Kingdom's exclusive economic zone.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-14T16:19:21.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443214/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443214/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Fisheries: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which military assets provide fisheries protection within the UK's exclusive economic zone.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443215","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>This information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-01-15T14:22:24.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443215/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443215/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Royal Regiment of Scotland: Reserve Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many of the total strength of (a) 6 SCOTS and (b) 7 SCOTS attended (i) more than 50 per cent and (ii) more than 75 per cent of regular duties in each year between 2012 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443216","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Ministry of Defence is procuring a Lightning II Integrated Training Centre (ITC) at its main operating base at RAF Marham. The ITC will house full mission simulators with the capability of simulating the full range of bases from which the F-35 may be required to operate.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-14T16:16:08.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443216/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443216/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Joint Strike Fighter Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to build facilities to simulate the possibility of the future F35B Lightning II aircraft operating in austere operating bases.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443217","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>On 18 October 1993, the then Secretary of State for Defence informed Parliament (Official Report, column 32): &quot;we have concluded that our previous requirement for a new stand-off nuclear weapon capability is not a sufficiently high priority to justify the procurement of a new nuclear system in the current circumstances. Instead, we will plan, after the WE177 eventually leaves service in the long term, on exploiting the flexibility and capability of the Trident system to provide the vehicle for the delivery of our sub-strategic deterrent.&quot;</p><br /><p>Also on 19 July 1993 (HC Deb vol 229 cc83-4W), the then Minister for Defence Procurement provided the following information about expenditure to evaluate options for the Future Theatre Nuclear Weapon:</p><br /><p>Expenditure to the end of March 1993 on studies of possible vehicles:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>£</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1989-90</p></td><td><p>928,518</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1990-91</p></td><td><p>1,372,329</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1991-92</p></td><td><p>1,870,285</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1992-93</p></td><td><p>2,658,471</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Information on costs incurred on the Future Theatre Nuclear Weapon warhead programme was withheld for reasons of national security. Those reasons no longer apply but this information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><br /><p><br></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-15T13:27:37.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443217/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443217/answer","Hansard Extracts  HOC 21550.docx","Hansard Extracts  HOC 21550.docx","Nuclear Weapons","Nuclear Weapons","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443217/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on what date the decision was made not to proceed with developing a future theatre nuclear weapon (FTNW); and how much had been spent on (a) the vehicle element and (b) the warhead element of the FTNW programme up to that point.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443218","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-12","<br /><br /><p>The Reserve Forces’ and Cadets’ Association for Northern Ireland (RFCA NI) is responsible for an ongoing campaign to recruit adult instructors for the Air Training Corps and Army Cadet Force in Northern Ireland. This is a highly effective campaign which has resulted in full staffing. Further details of the activities of RFCA NI can be found at the following address: <a href="http://www.reservesandcadetsni.org.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.reservesandcadetsni.org.uk/</a></p><br /><p>The Ministry of Defence is responsible for recruitment into the Reserve Forces. For information on the numbers of Reserve personnel stationed in Northern Ireland I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 20 October 2015 to Question 11478 to the hon. Member for East Antrim (Mr Wilson).</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-10-12/11478/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-10-12/11478/</a></p><br /><p><br></p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-01-12T17:20:46.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443218/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443218/answer","Hansard Extract 20 October 2015.docx","Hansard Extract 20 October 2015.docx","Reserve Forces: Northern Ireland","Reserve Forces: Northern Ireland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443218/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Cadets and Reserve Forces: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the outcome was of the recruitment campaign organised by the Reserve Forces and Cadet Association of Northern Ireland in Summer 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","21536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443219","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE) received a single Improvement Notice from the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) on 8 June 2015. This Improvement Notice remains open; the ONR and the AWE have agreed a set of actions that enable this to be closed by the due date of 30 September 2016.</p><p>No regulatory authority has taken enforcement action against the AWE in 2014 and 2015, and no warning letters have been issued.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-15T13:30:15.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443219/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443219/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","AWE: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what (a) enforcement action was taken and (b) warning letters were issue against the Atomic Weapons Establishment by regulatory authorities in 2014 and 2015; and which of those enforcement actions are ongoing.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443220","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>A further update will be published this year.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-14T16:18:41.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443220/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443220/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Trident","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans to publish the UK's Future Nuclear Deterrent: 2015 Update to Parliament.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443221","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>The cost of Project Phoebe was £20.1 million (excluding VAT).</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-15T13:33:04.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443221/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443221/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","AWE Aldermaston: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the costs were of repairing structural defects to the A45 facility at the Atomic Weapons Establishment (Project Phoebe).","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443222","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>Since 1 January 2014, there have been two occasions on which anomalies have been discovered in the labelling of explosives at the Atomic Weapons Establishment. In each case a small discrepancy was discovered through the checking and accounting process in place. In neither case were any explosive licence limits exceeded, and there was no requirement to notify the Authority or the Regulator.</p><p>On 14 August 2015, it was identified that a container labelled as containing 0.054 Kg of explosives actually contained 0.063 Kg.</p><p>On 6 January 2016, it was identified that a container labelled as containing 0.10716 Kg of explosives actually contained 0.0872 Kg.</p><p>The explosives concerned were Hazard Type 1.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-01-15T13:28:46.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443222/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443222/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","AWE: Explosives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on how many occasions since 1 January 2014 explosives stored at the Atomic Weapons Establishment have been found to be wrongly labelled; on what date it was discovered that such explosives were wrongly labelled; and what (a) types and (b) quantities of explosives were involved in each such case.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443223","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>Work is currently being undertaken by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) to produce a Socio-Economic Report for the Raasay Ranges. This is in addition to the assessment commissioned by the local fishing community. The MOD Report will be completed and made available in advance of the outcome of the Raasay Byelaw Review which is due to be finished later this year.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-01-14T17:01:18.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443223/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443223/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Fisheries: Hebrides","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, further to his letter referenced MSU/4/5/8 which is placed in the Library, whether and to what timescale his Department plans to commission its own socio-economic report in addition to the economic impact assessment commissioned by the fishing community; if he will publish results of such a report; and what the implications of such work are for the timescales for determining the proposed byelaw changes for the inner sound between Raasay and the mainland.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","21547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443224","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-15","<p>Finding TRF 195 from the Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator's assessment of Exercise Astral Climb 2012 called for documented arrangements to be reviewed and updated to reflect two changes in practice: the responsibility for the medical response and the monitoring instrumentation. This action was completed in August 2013. The finding also called for a review of Convoy and Station Nuclear Emergency Organisation Team response arrangements; this review was carried out in 2015.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-01-15T13:25:52.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443224/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443224/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Nuclear Installations: Emergencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what actions have been undertaken in response to finding reference TRF0195 of the Defence Nuclear Safety Regulator's assessment of the Astral Climb 12 nuclear emergency exercise; and on what dates each such action was closed out.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443225","Department for Education","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Government’s approach is to develop opportunities for everyone. This includes measures to improve literacy and numeracy, and the quality of teaching; targeting resource through the pupil premium to ensure every young person, regardless of birth or background, has the opportunity to realise their full potential.</p><br /><p>Inequality in relation to exclusion is a complex and longstanding issue. Many of the issues that underlie the inequalities seen in exclusion are inseparable from those that lead to other educational inequalities, including academic attainment. Removing the barriers to children engaging with education is fundamental to attendance, academic attainment, improving behaviour and reducing the need for exclusion.</p><br /><p>Through the pupil premium, schools receive additional funding to help them support their disadvantaged pupils, and have flexibility over how they use this to improve the progress and attainment of those pupils. In the current financial year, 59% of Gypsy and Roma pupils and 72% of Traveller pupils are eligible for the pupil premium, compared with 28% of all pupils.</p><br /><p>In 2012, the Government funded two local authorities (Cambridgeshire and Kent) to each appoint a Virtual Head Teacher to support schools in raising the attainment of GRT pupils, to increase awareness of the common issues faced by Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils and to help schools to overcome them. The findings of these pilots are available at <a href="https://www.learntogether.org.uk/Resources/Documents/Cambs%20VHT%20DfE%20final%20report.doc" target="_blank">https://www.learntogether.org.uk/Resources/Documents/Cambs%20VHT%20DfE%20final%20report.doc</a> and <a href="http://www.edukent.co.uk/images/uploads/misc_files/VHT_Kent_Final_report_GH.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.edukent.co.uk/images/uploads/misc_files/VHT_Kent_Final_report_GH.pdf</a>.</p><br /><p>The Department has also produced short case studies of schools that have been successful in improving the attendance and attainment of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils. These are available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/case-studies/gypsy-roma-and-traveller-pupils-supporting-access-to-education" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/case-studies/gypsy-roma-and-traveller-pupils-supporting-access-to-education</a>.</p><br /><p>Schools have duties under the Equality Act 2010 not to discriminate against pupils, including in the exclusion process. These duties are considered as part of the inspection process and complaints processes exist to consider individual complaints.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-15T14:50:39.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443225/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443225/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Pupil Exclusions: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to address the disproportionate number of exclusions from school of Gypsy, Roma and Traveller pupils.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","21520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443226","Department for Education","false","2016-01-14","<p>We are currently considering the Department's role in the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller Education Stakeholder Group. Officials will be writing to members of the group in the spring.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-14T17:19:28.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443226/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443226/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Education: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she will re-establish the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller Education Stakeholder Group; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","21519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443227","Department for Education","false","2016-01-12","<p>The specific information requested is not held by the Department for Education.</p><p>Under the National Curriculum, as updated in September 2014, cooking is now compulsory for pupils in Key Stages 1-3 in maintained schools. Children are taught about food, nutrition and healthy eating and how to cook a repertoire of dishes.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-12T17:51:29.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443227/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443227/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Food Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will estimate how many pupils are being taught how to cook in the 2015-16 academic year.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","21599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443228","Department for Education","false","2016-01-12","<p>The arrangement of foster care placements is the duty of local authorities. The regulatory framework for the provision of foster care placements is clear that local authorities must have access to sufficient placements to meet the needs of the children they look after.</p><p>The framework referred to above is clear that foster carers should not be economically disadvantaged as a consequence of carrying out their role on behalf of the local authority.</p><p>There is no specific provision for foster carers in council tax legislation. However, local authorities are able to grant council tax reductions to any individuals or groups as they see fit.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-01-12T17:36:17.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443228/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443228/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Foster Care: Council Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on local authorities offering council tax discounts to in-house foster carers but not to independent or agency foster carers looking after children in care from that authority; and what information she holds on which authorities have such arrangements.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","21460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443229","Department for Education","false","2016-01-14","<p>No jobs in either the Department for Education or any of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies or other accountable statutory bodies have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010, and no such jobs will be abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-14T17:27:54.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443229/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443229/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Department for Education: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443230","Department for Education","false","2016-01-12","<p>Registering new childcare providers is a matter for Ofsted. Her Majesty's chief inspector will be writing to the hon. Member about this matter. A copy of that letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><br />","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-01-12T17:40:04.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443230/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443230/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many childcare providers waited longer than 25 weeks to receive registration from Ofsted in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","21437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443231","Department for Education","true","2016-01-12","<p>Ofsted have run a number of pilot inspections since 2010:</p><ul><li>5 multi-agency child protection inspection pilots;</li><li>2 joint (with CQC) children looked after inspection pilots;</li><li>2 Integrated inspection pilots; and</li><li>1 Joint targeted area inspection, undertaken in November/December 2015.</li></ul><p>Following the pilot in November/December 2015, Ofsted intends to conduct up to six Joint Targeted Area Inspections by the summer of 2016.</p><p>There are 152 local authority children’s services departments. Of these three are rated ‘outstanding’, 53 are rated ‘good’, <del class="ministerial">39</del> <ins class="ministerial">36</ins> are rated ‘adequate’, <del class="ministerial">75</del> <ins class="ministerial">39</ins> are rated ‘Requires improvement’ and 21 are rated ‘Inadequate’. A table that has been attached to this answer sets out the most recent Ofsted rating for each local authority and indicates whether the authority is subject to intervention for its children’s social care services. All local authorities rated as ‘Inadequate’ are subject to intervention measures.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-12T17:58:50.143Z","2016-03-23T11:45:47.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443231/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443231/answer","21474 and 21475 appendix Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11.01.2016.docx","21474 and 21475 appendix Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11.01.2016.docx","Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 1 2016","Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 1 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443231/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443231/answer/previousversion/38541","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443231/answer/previousversion/38541","PQ21474 and PQ21475 appendix Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 01 2016.doc","Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 1 2016","60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which children's services departments are rated as (a) outstanding, (b) good, (c) requiring improvement and (d) inadequate; and which such departments are subject to intervention measures.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","21475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443232","Department for Education","false","2016-01-12","<p>As at 31 December 2015, there were 1468 men and 2026 women working in the Department for Education.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-12T17:54:44.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443232/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443232/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Department for Education: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many people of each gender work in her Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443233","Department for Education","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Leadership Equality and Diversity Fund supports groups of schools to design and deliver bespoke leadership activity to help increase the diversity of those leading England’s schools. Programmes can target any of the nine protected characteristics of the Equality Act 2010. The protected characteristics are age, disability, gender reassignment, marriage and civil partnership, pregnancy and maternity, race, religion or belief, sex, and sexual orientation.</p><p>In 2015-16 there are 40 projects. The full details and purpose of each project is available in the document, “Leadership Equality and Diversity Fund” published at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480857/leadership_equality_and_diversity_schools.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480857/leadership_equality_and_diversity_schools.pdf</a></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-01-12T17:41:54.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443233/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443233/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Leadership, Equality and Diversity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what grants have been made by the Leadership Equality and Diversity Fund; and for what purpose each such grant has been made.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","21472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443234","Department for Education","false","2016-01-12","<p>Local Safeguarding Children Boards (LSCBs) are funded through contributions from their partners as agreed locally, including local authorities, health services and the police. LSCBs publish details of these contributions in their annual reports, but these figures are not collated centrally. The Government does not provide ring-fenced funding for LSCBs.</p><p>On 14 December 2015, the Prime Minister announced that there would be a review of LSCBs. This review has now commenced and will report by the end of March 2016.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-01-12T17:43:57.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443234/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443234/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Children: Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what funding has been given to Local Safeguarding Children Boards in each year since 2010; and whether her Department plans to institute a nationally-defined funding formula for such boards.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","21473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443235","Department for Education","true","2016-01-12","<p>Ofsted have run a number of pilot inspections since 2010:</p><ul><li>5 multi-agency child protection inspection pilots;</li><li>2 joint (with CQC) children looked after inspection pilots;</li><li>2 Integrated inspection pilots; and</li><li>1 Joint targeted area inspection, undertaken in November/December 2015.</li></ul><p>Following the pilot in November/December 2015, Ofsted intends to conduct up to six Joint Targeted Area Inspections by the summer of 2016.</p><p>There are 152 local authority children’s services departments. Of these three are rated ‘outstanding’, 53 are rated ‘good’, <del class="ministerial">39</del> <ins class="ministerial">36</ins> are rated ‘adequate’, <del class="ministerial">75</del> <ins class="ministerial">39</ins> are rated ‘Requires improvement’ and 21 are rated ‘Inadequate’. A table that has been attached to this answer sets out the most recent Ofsted rating for each local authority and indicates whether the authority is subject to intervention for its children’s social care services. All local authorities rated as ‘Inadequate’ are subject to intervention measures.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-01-12T17:58:50.097Z","2016-01-14T15:09:36.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443235/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443235/answer","21474 and 21475 appendix Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11.01.2016.docx","21474 and 21475 appendix Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11.01.2016.docx","Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 1 2016","Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 1 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443235/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443235/answer/previousversion/38539","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443235/answer/previousversion/38539","PQ21474 and PQ21475 appendix Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 01 2016.doc","Table of Ofsted Inspection Ratings as at 11 1 2016","60","Education","Education","2016-01-07","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, which children's services departments have been subject to multi-agency inspections since 2010; and what the results were of each such inspection.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","21474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443236","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-01-12","<p>Neither the Department, nor any of its accountable statutory bodies, have had jobs abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent in the specified time period.</p><p><br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-01-12T15:22:37.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443236/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443236/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-07","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443237","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-14","<p>It is the duty of every local weights and measures authority to enforce the requirements of the Energy Performance of Buildings (England and Wales) Regulations 2012, as amended.</p><p>The attached table summarises the penalties that may be imposed by the enforcement authority or its authorised officer for breaches of the regulations regarding Energy Performance Certificates through serving a penalty charge notice. These are the financial penalties that are available to ensure that all private rented properties, both domestic and non-domestic, have an energy efficiency certificate.</p><p>Private sector landlords cannot serve a section 21 eviction notice on their tenant in respect of a property that was rented out since 1 October 2015 if they failed to provide their tenant with an Energy Performance Certificate at the start of the tenancy.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-14T16:59:19.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443237/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443237/answer","PQ 21434.docx","PQ 21434.docx","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443237/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-01-07","Private Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2015 to Question 19268, what (a) financial penalties and (b) other mechanisms are available to ensure that all private rented properties have an energy efficiency certificate.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","21434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443238","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-01-11","<p>The requirement on private rented sector landlords to improve their properties to a minimum energy efficiency rating of E from April 2018, subject to certain exemptions, will be enforced by individual local authorities. The Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property)(England and Wales) Regulations 2015 empower local authorities to enforce the provisions, including the power to impose compliance and penalty notices. Authorities will be able fine landlords up to £5,000 per property if they fail to comply with a compliance notice relating to a breach.</p><br /><p>Landlords who qualify for an exemption to meeting the minimum standard will be required to provide details to a centrally held register. Exemptions will be valid for a period of five years, after which time the landlord will once again need to try to improve the energy efficiency rating of the property. The register will be accessible to Local Authorities (and the general public) and will be audited by Local Authorities or DECC.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-01-11T17:29:11.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443238/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443238/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443238/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-07","Private Rented Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2015 to Question 19268, what financial penalties and other mechanisms are available to ensure that all private rented sector landlords improve their properties to a minimum energy efficiency rating of E from April 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Dan Poulter","Central Suffolk and North Ipswich","Dr   Poulter","21529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443239","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) is investigating the circumstances of the leak of natural gas from the Brae Alpha platform on 26th December 2015. It will ensure any lessons to be learnt to prevent a recurrence are shared with the operators of this and other platforms in the sector. If necessary it can use its formal enforcement powers to address significant shortcomings in systems and arrangements to manage risks.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-14T13:20:45.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443239/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443239/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443239/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Offshore Fixed Structures: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will investigate the circumstances surrounding the leak of natural gas at the Brae Alpha platform of 26 December 2015; and what steps he plans to take to ensure that a similar incident does not occur on that platform or any other offshore installation.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","21562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443240","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-01-13","<p>The incident on 26 December 2015 was a safety-related incident at an offshore oil and gas installation, the regulation of which falls within the Health and Safety Executive’s statutory remit under the Offshore Safety Directive.</p><br /> <br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-01-13T15:46:47.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443240/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443240/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443240/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-07","Offshore Fixed Structures: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what discussions her Department has had with the operators of the Brae Alpha platform following the gas leak on 26 December 2015 that resulted in the shutdown of that platform.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","21561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443241","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-01-12","<p>The regulation of the safety of offshore oil and gas installations in external waters is a matter for the Health and Safety Executive (HSE), working as part of the Offshore Safety Directive Regulator partnership. DECC and the Oil and Gas Authority are in regular contact with the industry and HSE regarding a range of offshore infrastructure issues, including the relationship between maintaining safety standards and reducing the cost of production. Together, we aim to ensure that industry resources are directed to maximising safe, sustainable production.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-01-12T12:03:02.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443241/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443241/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443241/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-07","Fossil Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what discussions she has had with the oil and gas industry on the relationship between maintaining safety standards and reducing the cost of production.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","21560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443242","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-01-12","<p>In the UK, we have an entirely different regulatory system to the US.</p><p>We have over 50 years of experience in safely conducting surface activities and constructing onshore gas wells, regulated by the Health &amp; Safety Executive and Environment Agency.</p><br /><p>Our tough regulations ensure on-site safety, prevent water contamination, mitigate seismic activity and air pollution. To reinforce our already robust regulations, the Infrastructure Act 2015 introduced a range of further requirements that must be met before an operator can carry out hydraulic fracturing in a responsible, sustainable and safe manner. These include the assessment of environmental impacts, groundwater monitoring, community benefits and prohibiting hydraulic fracturing in specified protected areas.</p><br /><p>The UK has one of the best track records in the world when it comes to protecting our environment while also developing our industries – and we’ve brought that experience to bear on the shale gas protections.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-01-12T12:09:45.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443242/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443242/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443242/answer",,,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-01-07","Methane","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what initial assessment she has made of the implications of the incident at Porter Ranch, California, for safety and engineering procedures and standards in the UK onshore unconventional gas extraction sector.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","21523"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443243","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government has no plans to make an assessment of the humaneness of hunting with dogs. However, in 1999 a Government Committee (the Burns Inquiry) was set up to examine the facts in the debate about hunting with dogs, including whether hunting with dogs is cruel. The findings of the inquiry were published on 9 June 2000 (<a href="http://www.huntinginquiry.gov.uk/mainsections/huntingframe.htm" target="_blank">www.huntinginquiry.gov.uk/mainsections/huntingframe.htm</a>).</p><br /><p>On 12 March 2001 Lord Burns stated: “… There was not sufficient verifiable evidence or data safely to reach views about cruelty. It is a complex area …&quot;. [Hansard 12 March 2001; col. 533</p><p><a href="http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2001/mar/12/hunting-bill" target="_blank">http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/lords/2001/mar/12/hunting-bill</a>].</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-13T16:07:32.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443243/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443243/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443243/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department plans to make an assessment of the humaneness of hunting with dogs.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","21544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443244","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-13","<p>We have extended the Farming Recovery Fund to allow eligible farmers in Lancashire and Yorkshire impacted by storm Eva, which hit over Christmas Day and Boxing Day, to be able to apply for support.</p><br /><p>The deadline for applications has been extended from 18 March 2016 to 1 April 2016 to provide further time for affected farmers to apply.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-01-13T17:43:43.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443244/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443244/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443244/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Floods: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to extend the Farming Recovery Fund to provide support for farmers in all areas affected by the recent flooding.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","21517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443245","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-13","<p>Implementation of the Water Framework Directive is devolved within the UK.</p><br /><p>Implementation of the Directive promotes, through river basin planning, an integrated approach to managing water and promotes local decisions in catchments to take account of the particular circumstances. Where parts of rivers are managed for certain uses (including flood protection), they are formally designated as ‘heavily modified’ and the management of those rivers must take account of those uses. In England, 1,105 of 3,767 rivers are designated as heavily modified; 781 of them because of their important role in providing flood protection.</p><p>Many of the actions needed to protect and improve the quality of the water environment (for instance restoring peat land, wetland creation and sustainable management of soils) also help to reduce flooding. The Directive also promotes sustainable flood risk prevention and flood management schemes. Consideration of natural flood management measures to slow, store and filter flood water can deliver additional social and environmental benefits when used along with traditional hard defences, and can increase resilience of communities to extreme events, both floods and drought. The ‘Slowing the Flow’ project in Pickering is an example of this.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-13T16:02:30.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443245/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443245/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443245/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Flood Control: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of the implementation of the EU Water Framework Directive 2000 on how floods have been controlled in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443246","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-15","<br /><p>The Vital Uplands report of 2009 was withdrawn by the previous Natural England Board and Management Team. Natural England, the Environment Agency, Defra and by academic institutions continue to closely monitor the complex science and evidence around upstream mitigation, through peatland, forestry and other natural measures. Some such measures have now been funded by the Government and piloted in schemes such as that in Pickering in Yorkshire. Natural upstream mitigation will be a key element of our planning at a catchment level, currently being taken forward through the Cumbrian Floods Partnership and our 25-year Environment Plan.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-15T13:44:01.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443246/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443246/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443246/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Hill Farming","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of implementing the Natural England report, Vital Uplands, published in 2009, in respect of restoration of deep upland vegetation to control hillside water run-off and valley flooding.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443247","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Secretary of State regularly discusses all relevant polices with her ministerial colleagues as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-14T15:47:27.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443247/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443247/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443247/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Hunting Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions she has had with her ministerial colleagues on the Hunting Act 2004.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","21521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443248","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government has no plans to establish a commission to examine the issue of hunting foxes with dogs. However, the Government continues to stand by its manifesto commitment to give Parliament the opportunity to repeal the Hunting Act on a free vote, with a government bill in government time.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-12T11:29:22.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443248/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443248/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443248/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will make it her policy to establish a commission to examine the issue of hunting foxes with dogs before bringing forward proposals for a vote in the House on that issue.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","21595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443249","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-13","<br /><p>Over 1,300 properties in Lancashire were affected by floods following Storm Eva with around 9,000 properties in England. These figures are subject to change and are based on local authority reporting.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-13T16:58:49.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443249/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443249/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443249/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate her Department has made of the number of households affected by floods on 26 December 2015 in (a) Lancashire and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","21602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443250","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-13","<p>We have made no assessment on the number of uninsured homes affected by flooding this winter.</p><br /><p>To help those affected by the current flooding, including the uninsured, the Government has announced nearly £200m to support recovery efforts. This includes funding to make properties more resilient to future flooding. In addition, we are taking action to protect people at the highest flood risk by making sure that everyone can access affordable flood insurance, regardless of where they live. Flood Re has now been set-up and it is expected to begin in April.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-13T16:52:55.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443250/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443250/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443250/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Floods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate her Department has made of the number of homes affected by flooding in winter 2015-16 that do not have insurance.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","21603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443251","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-12","<p>Defra has made no assessment of the effectiveness of legal provision relating to rights to grant or withhold access to caves. Cavers may use particular cave systems, where use has been traditional, or where the landowner allows or has given specific permission for cavers to do so.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-12T10:57:33.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443251/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443251/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443251/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Caves: Access","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of legal provision relating to rights to grant or withhold access to caves.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","21470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443252","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, its executive agencies non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies have no offices in Stoke-on-Trent, and therefore no jobs have been abolished since 2010 nor are any to be abolished or relocated by 2020.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-01-14T15:41:45.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443252/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443252/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443252/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443253","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-12","<p>Ministers and senior civil servants have not met or communicated with Ruimte voor de Rivier regarding long term flood prevention since June 2010.</p><br /><p>The Environment Agency has a good and highly valued relationship with the Dutch flood agency, Rijkswaterstaat, and has been actively engaging with them for many years on coastal, and asset management issues. This has been both bilaterally and through mutual networks. There is a strong exchange of knowledge between our organisations, supported by a non-legal Memorandum of Understanding. This also supports mutual cooperation during an incident, where appropriate.</p><br /><p>The Environment Agency was also grateful for the wider Dutch support offered during the 2013/14 flooding in the UK, with support from Dutch pumps and levee inspectors.</p><br />","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-01-12T11:25:18.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443253/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443253/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443253/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-01-07","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what meetings and communication Ministers and senior civil servants have had with Ruimte voor de Rivier regarding long-term flood prevention since June 2010.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","21476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443254","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-12","<br /><p>Oil workers operating oil production facilities in Daesh-controlled areas are treated as civilians, unless they directly participate in hostilities or otherwise can be shown to be members of Daesh. The UK takes appropriate measures to reduce the risk of collateral damage and we have a robust process in place to positively identify targets before we conduct airstrikes. To date there have been no reports of civilian casualties as a result of RAF airstrikes in Iraq or Syria.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-12T17:22:41.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443254/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443254/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many oil refinery workers have been killed as a result of UK airstrikes in Syria; and whether such workers are classed as civilian.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","21502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443255","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain -including at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting which was recently held in November 2015. The UK continues to encourage the Government of Bahrain to meet its human rights obligations and to honour all conventions to which it is a party. We welcome the progress made by Bahrain on their reform programme particularly in the areas of youth justice, the establishment and increasing effectiveness of the Ombudsman’s office, the Prisoner and Detainees’ Rights Commission and the reformed National Institute of Human Rights. We continue to work with the Government of Bahrain to ensure momentum and progress on its reforms, for the benefit of all Bahrainis.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-12T16:17:47.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443255/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443255/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Bahrain: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights situation in Bahrain; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","21467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443256","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain - including at the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting which was most recently held in November 2015. If we have specific concerns around convictions or sentencing, we raise these with the Government of Bahrain as part of our wider dialogue on human rights and reform.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-12T16:19:40.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443256/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443256/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Bahrain: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on the number of political prisoners held in that country; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","21468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443257","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","We are aware of the case of Hasan Mushaima and have raised it with the Government of Bahrain. The UK continues to encourage the Government of Bahrain to deliver on its international and domestic human rights commitments and to appropriately address all reports of ill-treatment of detainees. In parallel, we encourage all those with concerns about their treatment in detention to report these directly to the Ombudsman.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-12T16:21:58.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443257/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443257/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Hassan Mushaima","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his Bahraini counterpart on the continued detention and wellbeing of Hasan Mushaima.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","21469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443258","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>(a) None. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) does not have any staff in Stoke-on-Trent, and has not abolished or relocated any jobs from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010.</p><p>(b) None. The FCO’s non-departmental public departments and executive agencies do not have any staff in Stoke-on-Trent, and have not abolished or relocated any jobs from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-13T15:03:20.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443258/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443258/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443259","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>We are currently looking into unverified Iranian reports that a Saudi airstrike hit the Iranian Embassy in Sana’a. The Saudi government has denied that any such attack took place. The priority right now is for all parties to show restraint and responsibility in order to prevent the igniting of further hostilities. The British Government is urging all parties to show calm at this time and to work towards a de-escalation of growing tensions.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-01-12T16:47:51.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443259/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443259/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Iran: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the international legal implications of reports of Saudi Arabia bombing the Iranian Embassy in Sana'a; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","21464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443260","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","The UK government has regularly raised with the Saudi Arabian Government the need to comply with International Humanitarian Law (IHL) in Yemen. I raised the issue of compliance with IHL during my October visit to Saudi Arabia. We have also raised our concerns with the Houthis on the importance of compliance with IHL.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-01-12T17:29:06.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443260/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443260/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 January 2016 to Question 15523, when he last discussed alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen with his Saudi counterpart.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","21462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443261","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The UK keeps adherence to International Humanitarian Law (IHL) under constant review. The Ministry of Defence monitors alleged IHL violations, using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of IHL compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of information from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations. The UK government has regularly raised with the Saudi Government the need to comply with IHL in Yemen and we continue to engage with them on this. I raised the issue of compliance with IHL during my October visit to Saudi Arabia. We have also raised our concerns with the Houthis on the importance of compliance with IHL. It is important that open and transparent investigations are conducted into all incidents where it is alleged that IHL has been breached. We welcome the public announcement by Saudi Arabia to establish a fact finding committee into the alleged airstrike on MSF mobile clinic in Taiz on 2 December.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-01-12T17:33:10.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443261/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443261/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 January 2016 to Question 15523, when he last reviewed alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","21463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443263","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","We have not made any formal representations to the US Government or Congress. However, the Prime Minister, my right hon Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), has made clear that he completely disagrees with Mr Trump’s comments, which the Prime Minister described as “divisive, unhelpful and wrong”.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-01-18T13:35:34.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443263/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443263/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Donald Trump","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made representations to the US (a) government and (b) Congress on comments made by Republican presidential candidate Donald Trump on banning Muslims from entering the US.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","21426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443264","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>A stable and secure Middle East is a key UK priority. We are working with the international community to support those tackling short term conflict and promoting longer-term reform in the region. We believe that regional security initiatives can have an important role to play too.</p><p>We are not aware of any specific, new initiatives to create an independent regional centre for security dialogue in the Middle East, at the current time.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-18T15:31:57.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443264/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443264/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Middle East: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he plans to support initiative to the create an independent regional centre for security dialogue in the Middle East.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443266","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>It is a condition of their employment that members of the diplomatic service must be prepared to serve anywhere in the world at any time during their career, sometimes at very short notice. Those with children have a legal obligation as parents to ensure that their children receive a full-time education from the age of five years. Most parents prefer to take their children with them abroad, but in some of the 168 countries and territories where the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has UK based staff, we do not permit staff to take their children either for health or security reasons. In others, local schools of an acceptable standard are not available. It is longstanding practice that the FCO helps staff meet their potentially conflicting obligations by providing financial support for their children's education in the UK where staff choose this, or are obliged to do so given local conditions in the country to which they are posted.</p><p>Continuity of education is also an important factor, particularly at secondary level.</p><p>The FCO refunds standard term fees up to a ceiling which is reviewed annually. Where staff opt to send their children to more expensive schools, staff meet the difference in cost. The maximum amount the FCO will pay is determined by an independent survey conducted by ECA International, which is used by public and private sector employers whose staff work across the world. Various factors, including availability of places (sometimes at short notice) and proximity of other family members, influence which schools staff choose for their children.</p><p><br>FY UK School costs (CEA) Number of Children <br>2012/13 £14,926,061 700<br>2013/14 £13,704,118 (£13,162,823)*625 (604)*<br>2014/15 £12,943,134 (£12,391,079)*593 (570)*<br>*Cost to the FCO after reclaiming costs from other Government departments for their staff deployed overseas</p><p>We are unable to provide the 5 schools that had the highest spend in each of those years as to do so would entail checking individual files, which would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-18T14:59:32.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443266/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443266/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Armed Forces: Private Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much his Department spent on Continuity of Education Allowance in independent schools in financial year (a) 2012-13, (b) 2013-14 and (c) 2014-15; how many children were in receipt of that allowance in each of those years; and which five schools had the highest spend on that allowance in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","21577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443267","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>Following Adoption Day in October, Iran has been undertaking the nuclear actions required under the Joint Comprehensive Plan for Action, including recently shipping 12.5 tonnes of enriched uranium to Russia. Iran has almost completed removing the necessary 13,000 centrifuges and put plans in place to remove the core of the Arak plutonium reactor. The International Atomic Energy Agency will verify that Iran has undertaken all of the necessary steps to trigger Implementation Day.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-13T15:10:00.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443267/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443267/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Iran: Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the implementation to date of the Joint Comprehensive Plan for Action on the Iranian nuclear programme.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443268","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","We raise human rights concerns on a regular basis with the Lao government both bilaterally and through multilateral fora. As part of Laos’ Universal Periodic Review process starting in January 2015, and the EU-Laos Human Rights Dialogue in November 2015, we raised concerns regarding restrictions on the right to freedom of religion or belief. We will continue to look for opportunities to work with the Lao government to implement its human rights obligations and commitments, including those regarding respect for the rights of religious minorities.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-01-12T17:20:13.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443268/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443268/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Laos: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the government of Laos on the treatment of the Christian minority in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","21535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443269","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>The British Government remains firmly opposed to the use of the death penalty in all circumstances and in every country, including Saudi Arabia. The death penalty undermines human dignity and there is no evidence that it works as a deterrent. We continue to remind the Saudi authorities of our views on the death penalty at every suitable opportunity.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-18T14:56:10.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443269/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443269/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to page 3 of the HMG Strategy for Abolition of the Death Penalty 2010-2015, as revised in October 2011, what bilateral agreements his Department promotes between the Government and the government of Saudi Arabia on reducing the number of executions carried out as part of that government's judicial process.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","21549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443270","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>We urge all states to introduce a moratorium on use of the death penalty. We urge those which continue to impose the death penalty to respect EU and UN standards; to reserve the death penalty for the most serious crimes, that is, for nothing less serious than murder; to ensure that proper process is followed including opportunities for appeal and clemency and not to execute those who committed crimes when under 18, pregnant women or people with learning difficulties. The Government makes representations when these standards are not respected and urges reform. We fund projects which aim to increase compliance with these standards and actively support the abolitionist work of the UN and the EU, including through adoption of moratoria.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-01-18T16:04:11.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443270/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443270/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to Appendix Four of the HMG Strategy for Abolition of the Death Penalty 2010-15, as revised in October 2011, how his Department ensures that the EU minimum standards referred to are met in countries which maintain use of the death penalty as part of their judicial process.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","21546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443271","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>The British Government published in 2014 “Guidance on Overseas Security and Justice Assistance” which controls and restricts the supply of justice sector assistance to countries which retain the death penalty. The Government has also successfully urged the European Commission to introduce regulations banning the export of any equipment or chemicals intended to carry out executions.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-01-18T16:07:40.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443271/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443271/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Executive Summary of the HMG Strategy for Abolition of the Death Penalty 2010-2015, as revised in October 2011, what steps his Department is taking to help impose further restrictions on countries which continue to practise the death penalty as part of their judicial process; and what progress on the imposition of such restrictions has been made to date.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","21553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443272","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-01-14","<p>We do not provide combat training to the Burmese army. We do provide educational training which in 2015 included the Managing Defence in a Wider Security Context and Strategic Leadership Programmes, both delivered by the Defence Academy of the United Kingdom in partnership with Cranfield University. In addition, the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst delivered a Psychology of Leadership programme in Burma, and we have also provided English Language Training. We hold no information on whether any specific members of the Burmese Army who have received training from the UK have been involved in offensives in which war crimes may have been allegedly committed.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-01-14T16:18:05.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443272/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443272/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-01-07","Burma: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on whether any members of the Burmese army who have received training from the Government have been involved in military offensives in which war crimes have allegedly been committed against civilians.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","21564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443273","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>Using a range of funding tools, principally the Human Rights and Democracy Programme Fund, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has, since 2010, funded a number of non-governmental organisations to mount legal challenges to the use of the death penalty abroad both in specific cases and on matters of general principle. We do not fund the private legal costs of British nationals facing the death penalty, but we can refer cases to the FCO’s pro bono legal panel, where appropriate, to provide advice to the British national in question and their local lawyer on an entirely pro bono basis.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-01-18T16:08:11.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443273/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443273/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to page three of the HMG Strategy for Abolition of the Death Penalty 2010-2015, as revised in October 2011, what legal challenges to the mandatory death penalty his Department has been involved in involving (a) UK citizens and (b) non-UK citizens in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","21554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443274","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The UK’s support for military action is contingent on adherence to International Humanitarian Law (IHL). The Ministry of Defence monitors alleged IHL violations, using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of IHL compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of information from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations. We are also offering advice and training to Saudi Arabia to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with IHL. We are aware of reports on alleged violations of international humanitarian law (IHL) in Yemen by the Coalition and take these very seriously. We are also concerned by reports of alleged IHL violations by Houthi-Saleh and pro-government forces and again take these very seriously. The UK government has regularly raised with the Saudi Government the need to comply with IHL in Yemen and we continue to engage with them on this. I raised the issue of compliance with IHL during my October visit to Saudi Arabia. We have also raised our concerns with the Houthis on the importance of compliance with IHL. It is important that open and transparent investigations are conducted into all incidents where it is alleged that IHL has been breached. We welcome the public announcement by Saudi Arabia to establish a fact finding committee into the alleged airstrike on MSF mobile clinic in Taiz on 2 December.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-01-12T17:52:49.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443274/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443274/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 January 2016 to Question 15523, what assessment he has made of whether incidents of alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen have been investigated fully by each party involved in that conflict.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","21584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443275","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The UK’s support for military action is contingent on adherence to International Humanitarian Law (IHL). The Ministry of Defence monitors alleged IHL violations, using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of IHL compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of information from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations. We keep compliance under constant review. We are also offering advice and training to Saudi Arabia to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with IHL. I raised the issue of compliance with IHL during my October visit to Saudi Arabia. We have also raised our concerns with the Houthis on the importance of compliance with IHL.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-01-12T17:45:57.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443275/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443275/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 4 January 2016 to Question 15523, what assessment he has made of the credibility of assurances by Saudi Arabia that it is in compliance with international humanitarian law in the conflict with Yemen.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","21585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443276","Department of Health","false","2016-01-15","<p>The increased excess deaths in 2014-15 coincided with the circulation of a strain of flu, A(H3N2), that particularly affects older people. Cold snaps and other respiratory infections may also have contributed to an increase in excess mortality. There was evidence also that the flu vaccine provided reduced protection due to some drift of the circulating A(H3N2) virus.</p><br /><p>These observations were not unique to the United Kingdom, with 14 other European countries also reporting an increase in excess mortality. Throughout the last decade, there has generally been a good match between the strains of flu in the vaccine and those that subsequently circulate, highlighting the importance of flu vaccination for at risk groups, including older people and also the childhood flu vaccine programme, which when rolled out, aims to provide protection for both children, but also the general population.</p><br /><p>Public Health England has no such data available for North East England.</p><br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","21568","2016-01-15T12:14:06.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443276/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443276/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Death: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessments he has made of the reasons for the increase in excess winter mortality rates in England in the winter of 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","21569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443277","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>Psychiatric nurses are not identified separately in the Health and Social Care Information Centre’s (HSCIC) workforce statistics. Area of Work, which is identified, is purely the area, function or specialty where the work activity takes place. The attached table shows the number of nurses within the psychiatry area of work from September 2010 to September 2015, the midpoint of the financial year. The data is sourced from the HSCIC’s monthly workforce statistics.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-01-12T13:58:19.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443277/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443277/answer","PQ21586 table formatted.xlsx","PQ21586 table formatted.xlsx","Qualified Nurses within the Psychiatry area","Qualified Nurses within the Psychiatry area","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443277/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Psychiatric Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many psychiatric nurses were in post in each financial year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","21586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443278","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>It is the responsibility of the professional regulators to set the standards and outcomes for education and training and approve training curricula to ensure newly qualified healthcare professionals are equipped with the knowledge, skills and attitudes to provide high quality patient care. This may include training on conflict resolution, empathy, mental self-care and managing own stress.</p><br /><p>Health Education England has a leadership role in ensuring the service continues to invest in the ongoing education and training of all staff and a shared responsibility for investing in continuing professional development to promote service innovation and transformation. However, employers are ultimately responsible for continuing professional development of their employees.</p><br /><p>Employers also have a responsibility to ensure the wellbeing of their staff.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","21588","2016-01-12T14:48:49.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443278/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443278/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what training and professional development is given to (a) doctors, (b) nurses and (c) mental health professionals on (i) conflict resolution, (b) methodical empathy and (iii) mental self-care.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","21587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443279","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>It is the responsibility of the professional regulators to set the standards and outcomes for education and training and approve training curricula to ensure newly qualified healthcare professionals are equipped with the knowledge, skills and attitudes to provide high quality patient care. This may include training on conflict resolution, empathy, mental self-care and managing own stress.</p><br /><p>Health Education England has a leadership role in ensuring the service continues to invest in the ongoing education and training of all staff and a shared responsibility for investing in continuing professional development to promote service innovation and transformation. However, employers are ultimately responsible for continuing professional development of their employees.</p><br /><p>Employers also have a responsibility to ensure the wellbeing of their staff.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","21587","2016-01-12T14:48:50.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443279/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443279/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what training and professional development is given to (a) doctors, (b) nurses and (c) mental health professionals on managing their own stress levels.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","21588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443280","Department of Health","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Department does not collect data on how much is spent by local authorities on vulnerable adult transport.</p><br /><p>Social care is a key priority for this Government. This is why, against the context of tough public sector finances; we have taken steps to protect social care services. As announced in the Spending Review, the Government is giving local authorities access to £3.5 billion of new support for social care by 2019/20.</p><br /><p>This means local government has access to the funding it needs to increase social care spending in real terms by the end of the Parliament.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-13T15:28:50.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443280/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443280/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Vulnerable Adults: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of local authority funding reductions on the provision of transport for vulnerable adults.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443281","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Government received and analysed data from numerous sources when formulating the announcement in the Chancellor’s Autumn Statement. We will continue to work with a wide range of stakeholders including other Government departments, solicitors and insurers in taking forward the new reform package. The Government will consult on the detail of these measures in due course. The consultation will be accompanied by an impact assessment.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-01-15T11:11:28.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443281/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443281/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Personal Injury: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the changes to personal injury law and procedure announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015 on the level of costs and changes for treatment for personal injury resourced by the NHS; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443282","Department of Health","false","2016-01-14","<p>NHS England is currently developing a refined process for the prioritisation of proposed new investments in specialised services and highly specialised services.</p><br /><p>This continues to be worked up, including formation of potential criteria and weighting. NHS England is aiming to begin using this process in June 2016. The process will be made public once complete.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-14T14:28:24.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443282/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443282/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Medical Treatments: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish NHS England's decision making criteria for the assessment of highly specialised technologies.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","21563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443283","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government is fully committed to providing support for anyone who needs it, including those who have suffered child abuse, and aims to improve the data on prevalence of child sexual abuse so that commissioners are better able to ensure the most appropriate services are available. This includes improving available data on the prevalence of child abuse and related mental health issues, using the population-wide children and adolescent mental health survey, as well as a data collection specifically on the prevalence of child sexual abuse starting in certain targeted services.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-12T12:16:22.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443283/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443283/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2015 to Question 19356, if he will make it his policy to collect information on the proportion of people identified as having experienced child abuse who are diagnosed with a mental health condition as a young person or adult.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","21594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443284","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>This Government has no plans to collect this data centrally. The Government’s focus remains on promoting and supporting proper and effective multi-agency working and whole family approaches to assessment and support.</p><br /><p>This Government is committed to delivering the vision set out in <em>Future in mind</em> and is driving forward the transformation of children and young people’s mental health services to improve access and make services more widely available across the country so that, where possible, children can access high-quality support locally including vulnerable children which includes young carers.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-12T12:10:28.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443284/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443284/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20190, if he will make it his policy to collect centrally the number of (a) young carers accessing Children and Adolescene Mental Health Services (CAMHS) and (b) children provided with young carers assessments following contact with CAMHS.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","21593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443285","Department of Health","false","2016-01-14","<p>In 2014 NHS England published five clinical commissioning policies and policy statements for the routine of commissioning of new treatments, drugs or devices for specialised commissioning.</p><br /><p>In 2015 (up to November 2015), 38 such clinical commissioning policies and policy statements were published.</p><br /><p>Decisions for the 2015/16 commissioning round were due to be made in 2014 but this process was deferred to 2015 pending the outcome of public consultation on process.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-14T14:52:07.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443285/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443285/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Specialised Commissioning Oversight Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many commissioning policies were developed through the NHS England Specialised Commissioning Oversight Group in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","21575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443286","Department of Health","false","2016-01-15","<p>The increased excess deaths in 2014-15 coincided with the circulation of a strain of flu, A(H3N2), that particularly affects older people. Cold snaps and other respiratory infections may also have contributed to an increase in excess mortality. There was evidence also that the flu vaccine provided reduced protection due to some drift of the circulating A(H3N2) virus.</p><br /><p>These observations were not unique to the United Kingdom, with 14 other European countries also reporting an increase in excess mortality. Throughout the last decade, there has generally been a good match between the strains of flu in the vaccine and those that subsequently circulate, highlighting the importance of flu vaccination for at risk groups, including older people and also the childhood flu vaccine programme, which when rolled out, aims to provide protection for both children, but also the general population.</p><br /><p>Public Health England has no such data available for North East England.</p><br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","21569","2016-01-15T12:14:06.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443286/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443286/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Death: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in excess winter mortality rates in North East England in the winter of 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","21568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443287","Department of Health","false","2016-01-14","<p>NHS England is currently developing a refined process for the prioritisation of proposed new investments in specialised services and highly specialised services.</p><br /><p>The number of technologies to be routinely commissioned by NHS England will be determined by the new process.</p><p><br></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","21574","2016-01-14T14:37:24.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443287/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443287/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Medical Treatments: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many highly specialised technologies are awaiting assessment by NHS England which were not selected for consideration by NICE's highly specialised technology appraisal process.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","21573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443288","Department of Health","false","2016-01-14","<p>NHS England is currently developing a refined process for the prioritisation of proposed new investments in specialised services and highly specialised services.</p><br /><p>The number of technologies to be routinely commissioned by NHS England will be determined by the new process.</p><p><br></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","21573","2016-01-14T14:37:24.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443288/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443288/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Medical Treatments: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many highly specialised technologies are currently being assessed by the NHS England highly specialised technologies assessment process.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","21574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443289","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>The information requested is in the attached tables.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-12T15:26:20.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443289/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443289/answer","PQ21600 Table.xlsx","PQ21600 Table.xlsx","End of financial year budget surpluses or deficits","End of financial year budget surpluses or deficits","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443289/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","NHS Trusts: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the end of financial year budget surpluses or deficits was for each health trust in London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","21600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443290","Department of Health","false","2016-01-20","<p>Information on cancelled elective operations is published quarterly. The attached table shows how many elective operations were cancelled in England, London and each health trust in England in each quarter since 2010. Information on the number of cancelled elective operations as a percentage of elective admissions is only published for England.</p><br /><p>The number and proportion of cancelled operations remains low in the context of the millions of operations performed in the National Health Service each year. Compared to 2009/10, in 2014/15 there were 1.6 million more operations. The proportion of cancelled elective operations in the first two quarters of 2015/16 was 0.8% which is the same as the first two quarters of 2009/10.</p><br /><p>Health is a devolved matter in Wales.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-20T16:36:56.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443290/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443290/answer","PQ21601 Table.xlsx","PQ21601 Table.xlsx","Cancelled elective operations","Cancelled elective operations","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443290/answer","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443290/answer/previousversion/38542","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443290/answer/previousversion/38542",,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Surgery: Waiting Lists","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of elective operations were cancelled in (a) England and Wales, (b) London and (c) each health trust in England in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","21601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443291","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>A policy for the provision of Everolimus for Tuberous Sclerosis forComplex Related Renal Angiomyolipoma anda policy for the provision of Everolimusfor SubependymalGiant Cell Astrocytoma are currently in development. Once completed, each policy will need to be considered by the relevant clinical panels, the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group and the Specialised Commissioning Oversight Group.</p><br /><p>It is NHS England’s intention that the policies will be published by the end of the financial year.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-12T15:07:01.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443291/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443291/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to made the drug Everolimus available on the NHS for treating the subependymal giant cell astrocytoma form of tuberous sclerosis complex.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","21598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443292","Department of Health","false","2016-01-15","<p>Information about the number of jobs that (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020 is set out in the attached tables. The information about non-Departmental public bodies, executive agencies, and other accountable statutory bodies is not held centrally by the Department and their information, as indicated below, has been provided by those bodies.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-15T13:36:19.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443292/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443292/answer","pq21449 table.docx","pq21449 table.docx","Abolished or relocated jobs from Stoke-on-Trent","Abolished or relocated jobs from Stoke-on-Trent","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443292/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Department of Health: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443293","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. Information is available on the percentage of patients that were admitted, transferred or discharged within four hours of arriving at each accident and emergency department in London in December by year. December 2015 data has not been collected yet. This can be found at the following website:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/</a></p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-12T17:45:35.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443293/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443293/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of patients were seen within four hours of arriving at each A&E department in London in December (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014 and (f) 2015.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","21503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443294","Department of Health","false","2016-01-12","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. Information is available on the number of patients spending more than 12 hours from decision to admit to admission in each accident and emergency department in London by year. This can be found at the following website:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-01-12T17:46:26.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443294/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443294/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Accident and Emergency Departments: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many delays of over 12 hours there were in each A&E department in London in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","21504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443295","Department of Health","false","2016-01-14","<p>National Programmes of Care boards do not approve or decline proposed investments in specialised services.</p><p>Decisions on proposed investments are made by NHS England's Specialised Commissioning Oversight Group and the Specialised Commissioning Committee following recommendations from the Clinical Priorities Advisory Group.</p><p>National Programmes of Care boards provide assurance that proper process has been followed in the development of proposals for consideration.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-14T14:42:44.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443295/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443295/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of medicines selected by NHS England Clinical Reference Groups for the development of commissioning policies have been (a) approved and (b) not approved by each Programme of Care board.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","21509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443296","Department of Health","false","2016-01-14","<p>In 2014, five treatments commencedevaluation under NHS England's Commissioning through Evaluation programme.</p><br /><p>In 2015, six treatments commenced evaluation under NHS England's Commissioning through Evaluation programme.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-01-14T14:32:02.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443296/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443296/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Medical Treatments: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many technologies have been assessed through NHS England's commissioning through evaluation process in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","21510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443297","Department of Health","false","2016-01-13","<p>The issue of transport for vulnerable people is spread across Government, including the Department for Work and Pensions, the Department for Transport, the Department for Communities and Local Government and the Ministry of Defence.</p><br /><p>The funding for transport for vulnerable people in the Department of Health’s policy remit is provided by local authorities and clinical commissioning groups, who do not break down spend in this way. The Department of Health does not independently collect data on how much is spent on vulnerable adult transport.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-01-13T15:33:10.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443297/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443297/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-01-07","Vulnerable Adults: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding his Department provides for vulnerable adult transport.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443298","Home Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Home Office is committed to publishing data on the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme as part of the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The next set of figures will be in the quarterly release on 25 February 2016 and will cover the period October - December 2015.</p><p>This information will not show where refugees have been resettled, as resettlement under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme by local authorities is voluntary. It is a matter for each local authority to decide whether they want to publish the fact of their participation and the numbers of refugees they take.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-01-13T17:01:21.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443298/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443298/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Syrian refugees were resettled in each (a) region and (b) parliamentary constituency in the last 12 months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","21496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443299","Home Office","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Department records actual staffing levels, but does not centrally record the number of jobs by location. Actual staffing levels for (a) the Department, between March 2010 and March 2015, have slightly reduced (less than 10 FTE¹) in Stoke-on-Trent. However, this does not necessarily mean that posts have been abolished or relocated as a consequence.</p><p>The Department is still planning its workforce requirements for 2020 in line with the Spending Review settlement; this level of detail is not yet known.</p><p>(b) For the Department’s executive non-departmental public bodies and statutory bodies, there have been no staff or offices based in Stoke-on-Trent during this period. The Department’s executive non-departmental Public Bodies are:</p><p>• the Independent Police Complaints Commission;</p><p>• the Gangmasters Licensing Authority;</p><p>• the Office of the Immigration Services Commissioner;</p><p>• the Security Industry Authority; and</p><p>• the Disclosure and Barring Service</p><p>None of the Department’s Advisory and Tribunal NDPBs employ staff or have offices in Stoke-on-Trent.</p><p>¹Data Source: Data View, the Home Office's single source of Office for National Statistics compliant monthly snapshot corporate human resources data Period Covered: Figures are as at 31 March each year.</p><p>Extraction Date: 1st April each year</p><p>Organisational Coverage: March-10 - Figures include core Home Office and the Executive Agencies; United Kingdom Border Agency, Identity and Passport Service and the Criminal Records Bureau March -15 - Figures include core Home Office (including Border Force, UK Visas &amp; Immigration, Immigration En-forcement and Her Majesty's Passport Office.) Employee Coverage: Data is based on headcount and FTE of all current paid and unpaid civil servants as at 31st March each year</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-11T15:27:30.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443299/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443299/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Home Office: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443300","Home Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>The Government has a policy of not routinely commenting on individual immigration or exclusion cases.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-18T15:40:21.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443300/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443300/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Donald Trump","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the applicability to Donald Trump of her Department's guidelines on excluding hate speakers from entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","21427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443301","Home Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>HM Government does not routinely comment on assessments of alleged extremist behaviour by individuals. Tackling the threat that extremism poses to all UK communities is at the heart of HMG’s Counter-Extremism Strategy, and we are working in partnership with communities across the country to do so.</p><p>In July 2015, the Prime Minister charged Louise Casey with carrying out a review of ways to boost integration in UK communities to combat the divisive threat of extremism. An interim report for the review is due to be published in the early part of this year.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-18T12:30:09.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443301/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443301/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","US President: Candidates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the potential threat to minority communities in the UK of language used by US presidential election candidates which her Department defines as extreme.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","21428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443302","Home Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>A non -European Economic Area national may be refused entry to the UK, if, from information available the person’s exclusion is considered to be conducive to the public good. Each decision is made on a case by case basis taking into account all the relevant factors.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-01-14T16:25:11.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443302/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443302/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Exclusion Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has a policy on US  presidential candidates entering the UK who use hate speech.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","21425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443303","Home Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Animals in Science Committee (ASC) are responsible for providing impartial, balanced and objective advice to Ministers relating to the Animals (Scientific Procedures) Act 1986 (ASPA). The Committee is not responsible for granting licences. Under Section 9 of ASPA, the Secretary of State may consult the Committee regarding licence applications. Current policy requires referral of the following categories of project licence application:</p><p>• the use of wild-caught non-human primates;</p><p>• the use of cats, dogs, equidae or non-human primates in severe procedures;</p><p>• use of endangered species;</p><p>• projects with major animal welfare or ethical implications;</p><p>• projects involving the use of admixed embryos falling into category 3 of the Academy of Medical Science report on Animals Containing Human Material and category 2 where the predominance of an admixed embryo is unclear or uncertain;</p><p>• projects which may invoke any of the ‘safeguard clauses’ in the Directive with respect to the purpose of primate use, proposals for the use of a great ape, or proposals to cause long-lasting pain, suffering or distress that cannot be ameliorated; or</p><p>• projects of any kind raising novel or contentious issues, or giving rise to serious societal concerns.</p><p>In 2014, the most recent year for which we have data available, the ASC provided advice on four project licences. These were subsequently granted by the Home Office. The numbers of licences the ASC provided advice on in 2015 will be published in the ASC Annual Report later this year.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-01-13T16:59:20.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443303/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443303/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443303/answer/previousversion/38429","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443303/answer/previousversion/38429",,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Animal Experiments: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many licences for experimentation with animals the Animals and Science Committee granted in the most recent year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","21581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443304","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-13","<p>For the past four years Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) Travel Advice has consistently advised against all travel to Yemen. We recommend that British nationals in Yemen leave immediately. In addition to ongoing fighting, there remains a very high threat of kidnap and unlawful detention from militia groups, armed tribes, criminals and terrorists. The operations of our Embassy in Sana’a have been suspended since February 2015, which makes it difficult to provide any assistance in country. The FCO would not usually be responsible for facilitating contact between family members in a conflict, but as far as we are aware telephone communication is still possible in some areas.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-01-13T15:08:43.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443304/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443304/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-01-07","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assistance his Department provides for members of the Yemeni community in the UK to contact or find out information on relatives in Yemen affected by the civil war in that country.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","21528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443305","Home Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>Protecting women and girls from violence and supporting victims and survivors of domestic abuse and sexual violence remain key priorities for the Government. We will continue to improve the protection for victims and to bring offenders to justice.</p><p>The Home Office has been working with a number of relevant Government Departments to assess what processes and guidance are currently used to protect the addresses and personal information of vulnerable persons and victims of crime. We are now developing a voluntary code of practice to address the identified gaps.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-01-14T16:29:39.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443305/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443305/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Government's publication, Call to End Violence against Women and Girls' Action Plan 2014, published in March 2014, what progress has been made on putting in place a new code of practice to ensure that safe addresses of victims of domestic and sexual abuse are protected; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","21527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443306","Home Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>Since 20 May 2015, the National Crime Agency has been operating with full powers in Northern Ireland. The Crime and Courts Act 2013 (National Crime Agency and Proceeds of Crime) (Northern Ireland) Order 2015 requires the Northern Ireland Policing Board to monitor the exercise of the functions of the National Crime Agency in Northern Ireland. The interim Memorandum of Understanding between the National Crime Agency and the Northern Ireland Policing Board states the Board is required, not later than six months after the end of each financial year, to issue a report relating to the policing of Northern Ireland for the next financial year. The report will include an assessment of the exercise of the functions of the NCA in Northern Ireland. It further requires the Director General of the National Crime Agency to attend the Northern Ireland Policing Board and, in order to assist them, the National Crime Agency is to provide, on a quarterly basis, performance reporting on the exercise of the NCA’s functions in Northern Ireland which will be aligned to the key threat areas in the National Control Strategy, as outlined in the NCA’s Annual Plan. The NCA is committed to playing its role in tackling serious and organised crime in Northern Ireland.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-01-12T15:41:13.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443306/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443306/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","National Crime Agency: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she plans to make an assessment of the performance of the National Crime Agency in its first year of full operation in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","21537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443307","Home Office","false","2016-01-14","<p>The use of Census categories for ethnicity is assessed each year as part of the Home Office’s process of agreeing each year’s Annual Data Requirement (ADR) of mandatory collections of statistical data from the police. This process includes consideration of the need, use, burden and data quality issues for each data collection. The National Police Chiefs Council (NPCC) have previously advised against the transition to the new Census categories due to the significant burden that this would place on forces to change IT systems and processes.</p><p>The ADR collections currently use the Census 2001 ethnicity framework, and there are no plans at present to move to the Census 2011 framework, which would add a separate category of ‘Gypsy or Irish Traveller’.</p><p>The guidance given to police forces on providing data to the Home Office is based on the Census 2001 ethnicity framework. It is, however, a decision for individual forces as to how they monitor and record ethnicity data for their own purposes.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-14T17:56:08.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443307/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443307/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidance has been issued to police forces on monitoring and recording Gypsy and Traveller status as separate ethnic categories.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","21518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443308","Home Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>Individuals suspected of terrorism-related offences can be arrested under the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 (PACE) or the Terrorism Act 2000 (TACT). The decision on which power of arrest to use is an operational judgement for police, and will depend on the circumstances of the case.</p><p>Individuals arrested under TACT cannot be released on police bail. By contrast, those suspected of terrorism-related offences arrested under PACE must be bailed once the grounds for detention no longer apply. Figures for the number of terrorism-related suspects on police bail that have been ordered to relinquish their passports, or have relinquished their passports, are not collected.</p><p>As the Secretary of State for the Home Department said in the House on 05 January 2016, figures for the number of people who have absconded whilst on police bail for terrorism offences are also not collected.</p><p>Figures for those who fail to surrender to bail are collected, but these figures are not separated into categories of offence. These figures are publically available and can be found as follows: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","21512","2016-01-18T17:54:59.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443308/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443308/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many terrorism-related suspects on police bail have (a) been ordered to relinquish and (b) relinquished their UK passports since January 2013.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","21511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443309","Home Office","false","2016-01-18","<p>Individuals suspected of terrorism-related offences can be arrested under the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 (PACE) or the Terrorism Act 2000 (TACT). The decision on which power of arrest to use is an operational judgement for police, and will depend on the circumstances of the case.</p><p>Individuals arrested under TACT cannot be released on police bail. By contrast, those suspected of terrorism-related offences arrested under PACE must be bailed once the grounds for detention no longer apply. Figures for the number of terrorism-related suspects on police bail that have been ordered to relinquish their passports, or have relinquished their passports, are not collected.</p><p>As the Secretary of State for the Home Department said in the House on 05 January 2016, figures for the number of people who have absconded whilst on police bail for terrorism offences are also not collected.</p><p>Figures for those who fail to surrender to bail are collected, but these figures are not separated into categories of offence. These figures are publically available and can be found as follows: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","21511","2016-01-18T17:54:59.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443309/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443309/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-01-07","Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many terrorism-offence related suspects on police bail are understood by her Department to have broken bail and left the UK since January 2013.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","21512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443310","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-13","<p>Neither DFID nor its non-departmental public bodies have had, nor plan to have, any jobs based in Stoke-on-Trent during the periods in question.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-01-13T17:32:15.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443310/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443310/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-07","Department for International Development: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) its non-departmental public body, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443311","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-12","<p>In the financial year 2015/16 DFID’s latest Operational Plan budgets are £47 million in Jordan and £40 million in Iraq.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-01-12T14:16:00.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443311/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443311/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-07","Middle East: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much is allocated in her Department's operational plan budget for projects in (a) Jordan and (b) Iraq for 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443312","Department for International Development","false","2016-01-12","<p>DFID provides quarterly reports to the Office of National Statistics (ONS). The information provided at 31 December was as follows:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Gender</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Headcount</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>914</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>1152</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2066</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-01-12T14:39:52.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443312/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443312/answer",,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-01-07","Department for International Development: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many people of each gender work in her Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443313","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-14","Within the Ministry of Justice, only the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) and HM Courts and Tribunals Service (HMCTS) have offices within the Stoke-On-Trent postal address. There is one Juvenile Centre with a Stoke-On-Trent postal address, HMYOI Werrington. No posts have been abolished or relocated since 2010. There are currently no plans to abolish or relocate any posts by 2020. There are three National Probation Service (NPS) locations with a Stoke-on-Trent postal address. The NPS has only existed from 1 June 2014. Since that date there are no records of any posts being abolished or any relocation activity in the NPS Midlands Division which includes Stoke-on-Trent. There is an organisational change programme within the National Probation Service, that is ongoing and that will impact all area of NPS activity. It is too early to define the impact on a particular geographical location. HMCTS are unable to disaggregate information collected for the North Staffordshire area, so the following includes staff based within Stoke-on-Trent and Newcastle-under-Lyme. Since 2010, there has been a net reduction of 8 posts. There are currently no plans to further change the staffing in the North Staffordshire area.","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-14T14:33:38.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443313/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443313/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Ministry of Justice: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443314","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-12","<p>In the last 12 months for which data is available (December 2014 – November 2015), £91,172.45 was paid directly to Rentokil Initial Plc. Rentokill provide a range of services to the department in addition to pest control. £66,961.94 of the total was paid to Rentokill Initial Pest Control, and in the same period £525.88 was also paid to Killgerm Group Ltd for pest control services, a total of £67,487.82.</p><br /><p>This has reduced from £1,503,530.40 spent with Rentokil Initial Plc in 2010, of which £109.923.50 was with Rentokil Initial Pest Control. An additional £3,529.44 was paid to pest control companies in that year, making a total of £113,452.94.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-01-12T17:48:34.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443314/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443314/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Ministry of Justice: Pest Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department has paid to (a) Rentokil and (b) other pest control companies in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443315","Attorney General","false","2016-01-13","<p>Section 51 of the Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 creates two offences:</p><p>S.51(1) creates an offence directed at acts against a person who assists in an investigation of an offence or who is a witness or potential witness or juror or potential juror whilst an investigation or trial is in progress</p><p>S.51(2) creates an offence directed at acts against a person who assisted in an investigation of an offence or who was a witness or juror after an investigation or trial has been concluded.</p><p>The records held by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) identify the number of offences in which a prosecution commenced and reached a first hearing in the magistrates’ courts, rather than the number of defendants prosecuted. A single defendant may be prosecuted for multiple offences.</p><p>The number of offences charged under s.51(1) and s.51(2) are as follows:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>2010-2011</p></td><td><p>2011-2012</p></td><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>2014-2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 51(1)</p></td><td><p>Intimidate a witness / juror</p></td><td><p>3,275</p></td><td><p>2,630</p></td><td><p>2,148</p></td><td><p>2,066</p></td><td><p>2,202</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 51(2)</p></td><td><p>Do an act which harmed a witness / juror</p></td><td><p>102</p></td><td><p>166</p></td><td><p>99</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Criminal Justice and Public Order Act 1994 51(2)</p></td><td><p>Threaten a witness / juror</p></td><td><p>240</p></td><td><p>172</p></td><td><p>118</p></td><td><p>122</p></td><td><p>129</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>The proportion of CPS cases that result in a guilty plea has increased from 67.2% in 10/11 to 74.5% in 14/15 which means that there are fewer cases that are likely to be subject to the sorts of acts covered by s.51(1) during the course of the prosecution.</p><p>Also, s.51(1) covers intimidation of juror or potential jurors. The number of crown court trials have also been reducing over the period in question by 9.5%, again resulting in fewer cases where S.51(1) offences are likely to apply.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-01-13T15:14:30.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443315/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443315/answer",,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-01-07","Juries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, pursuant to the Answer of 5 January 2016 to Question 20564, how many people were charged with jury (a) intimidation and (b) tampering in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443316","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-23","<p>I refer the honourable member to the answer which I gave in PQ 21339, answered on 23<sup>rd</sup> February 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-23T13:14:24.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443316/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443316/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Ministry of Justice: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many press and public relations staff are employed by (a) his Department, (b) HM Courts and Tribunal Service, (c) HM Prison Service, (d) the Legal Aid Agency and (e) the National Offender Management Service; how many of those employees are paid more than (i) £50,000 and (ii) £100,000; and what the total expenditure was on press and public relations by each of those organisations in the most recent year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","21457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443317","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-14","<p>The data to answer this question is currently unavailable. The Ministry of Justice publishes data on incidences of release on temporary licence and the number of prisoners released on ROTL on a quarterly basis. The data is collated a quarter in arrears and published after quality assurance. Data for the fourth quarter of 2015 will be published on 28 April 2016.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-14T14:35:00.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443317/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443317/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many serving prisoners were not in prison on 25 December 2015; what offences were committed by each such offender; and how many such offences were in what category of violent offences against the person offences.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","21530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443318","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-01-12","<p>The number of men and women working in my Department as of January 2016 is as follows:</p><p>Male – 57</p><p>Female – 69</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-01-12T13:31:31.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443318/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443318/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-01-07","Northern Ireland Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many people of each gender work in her Department.","false","Biography information for Liz Kendall","Leicester West","Liz Kendall","21479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443319","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>The Government continues to work with a wide range of stakeholders in taking forward the whiplash reform package announced by the Chancellor in his Autumn Statement in November 2015. Officials met with representative bodies for claimant solicitors in December 2015 and a ministerial meeting is planned for the end of January 2016. They will have a further opportunity to comment when we consult on the detail of the reforms in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-01-15T11:19:13.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443319/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443319/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will meet with representative bodies of people acting for personal injury complainants to discuss the outcome of his discussions with the insurance industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21525"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443320","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government has implemented measures to encourage cleaner and more fuel efficient HGVs including through the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation, the £11m Low Carbon Truck Trial, and our £25m Advanced Biofuels Demonstration Competition. The Department for Transport is currently leading a review of options to further reduce CO<sub>2</sub> emissions from the freight sector.</p><br /><p>In December 2015 the Government published the UK air quality plan for nitrogen dioxide. Under this plan some older polluting vehicles, including lorries, will be discouraged from entering a number of city centres as one of a number of measures that will ensure the UK meets legal limit values outside London by 2020. Together with the existing Low, and forthcoming Ultra Low, Emission Zone in London, and other complementary measures in the Capital, this will encourage the uptake of lower emission HGVs.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-13T15:09:47.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443320/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443320/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-07","Large Goods Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is considering to reduce (a) CO2 and (b) NOx emissions for HGVs (i) domestically and (ii) at EU Level.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","21545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443321","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-13","<p>The longest length of lorry allowed on UK roads, including urban areas, is the road train at 18.75m. This is the maximum authorised length of lorry that the General Circulation Directive permits for national and international traffic. The Department is currently trialing longer semi-trailers (which are up to 2m longer than standard sized articulated lorries) although these are shorter than the road trains that are already in circulation across EU roads.</p><br /><p>Local authorities have powers under Sections 1 &amp; 2 of the Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984, to exclude heavy goods vehicles either generally or at specified times from roads for which they are considered to be unsuitable.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-13T15:13:43.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443321/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443321/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-07","Large Goods Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the use of longer-length or mega lorries in (a) the UK and (b) urban areas.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","21565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443322","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government recognises the strategic importance of supporting sustainable aviation fuels in order to reduce carbon emissions in the aviation sector, and drive the development of an advanced biofuels industry in the UK. Waste-derived fuels, such as those that the GreenSky project aim to produce, hold real potential for UK growth and jobs, as well as for our energy security and balance of payments.</p><br /><p>The GreenSky project was eligible to enter the Department’s recent Advanced Biofuel Demonstration Competition which has provided £25m of financial support to help develop sustainable biofuels. The competition attracted a wide range of strong proposals and following a thorough assessment process the GreenSky bid was unsuccessful.</p><br /><p>I have met with British Airways to discuss the GreenSky project. We will continue regular contact as British Airways pursue this excellent initiative to develop waste-derived jet fuel.</p><br /><p>The Transport Energy Taskforce, made up of a broad range of expert stakeholders, including British Airways, made recommendations last year, including making aviation biofuels eligible for rewards under the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation. We intend to include proposals on this in a public consultation this year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T14:39:04.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443322/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443322/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-07","Aviation: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons the Government has not given financial and other support to British Airways' Green Sky project; and what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the potential cancellation of that project on the aviation industry's sustainable aviation agenda.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","21516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443323","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-01-15","<p>Driving offences can have devastating consequences for victims and their loved ones, which is why tough sentences are available to the courts. It is our intention to consult on sentencing proposals, including driving, before the end of this year.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-01-15T11:07:02.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443323/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443323/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-01-07","Road Traffic Offences: Reviews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to commence its review of driving offences; when he plans that the public consultation on that review will take place; and what timetable he has set for the completion of that review.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","21522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443324","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-14","<p>In the Department for Transport itself, no posts have been based in Stoke-on-Trent since 2010.</p><br /><p>The Department’s Executive Agencies (Maritime and Coastguard Agency, Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency, Vehicle Certification Agency and Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency) have had no posts based in Stoke-on-Trent since 2010, other than the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency, who respond as follows:</p><br /><p>As part of the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency’s (DVSA) testing transformation programme, which has the aim of taking testing closer to the customer, DVSA’s Goods Vehicle Testing Station (GVTS) in Stoke-on-Trent was closed in April 2015. Twenty nine roles were based at this testing station. The staff previously based at the station are still working for DVSA in the area; twenty four of these roles are now based at other DVSA sites and the remaining five staff are being redeployed to other roles in DVSA. There are currently no plans to close any further DVSA Good Vehicle Testing Stations (GVTS) or Driving Test Centres (DTC) in the Stoke-on-Trent area between now and 2020.</p><br /><p>We are not aware of any jobs being based in Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 in the wider accountable statutory bodies.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-01-14T16:03:50.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443324/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443324/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-07","Department for Transport: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443325","Department for Transport","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Department has retested three of the VW Group vehicles for which the UK provided type approval. These tests have confirmed that the extended test programme announced by the Secretary of State on 10 November can identify defeat device strategies. The testing of vehicles is underway and a report of the findings will be published in the spring.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-01-12T14:32:58.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443325/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443325/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-01-07","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information he holds on how many Volkswagen vehicles have been re-tested for emissions since September 2015.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","21439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443326","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>The impact of the work allowance change cannot be considered in isolation – it is part of a broader package of measures announced at the Summer Budget, such as the increase to the personal tax allowance and introduction of the national living wage, which strengthens incentives to find work and better paid jobs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","21430 ; 21431 ; 21432 ; 21433","2016-01-13T16:59:49.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443326/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443326/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment his Department has carried out on the effects of reductions in universal credit work allowance on (a) incentives to work and (b) the number of hours worked.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","21429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443327","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>The impact of the work allowance change cannot be considered in isolation – it is part of a broader package of measures announced at the Summer Budget, such as the increase to the personal tax allowance and introduction of the national living wage, which strengthens incentives to find work and better paid jobs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","21429 ; 21430 ; 21432 ; 21433","2016-01-13T16:59:49.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443327/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443327/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment his Department has carried out on the effects of reductions in the universal credit work allowance on carers.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","21431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443328","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>The impact of the work allowance change cannot be considered in isolation – it is part of a broader package of measures announced at the Summer Budget, such as the increase to the personal tax allowance and introduction of the national living wage, which strengthens incentives to find work and better paid jobs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","21429 ; 21430 ; 21431 ; 21433","2016-01-13T16:59:49.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443328/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443328/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment his Department has carried out on the effects of reductions in the universal credit work allowance on employees of his Department.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","21432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443329","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>The impact of the work allowance change cannot be considered in isolation – it is part of a broader package of measures announced at the Summer Budget, such as the increase to the personal tax allowance and introduction of the national living wage, which strengthens incentives to find work and better paid jobs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","21429 ; 21431 ; 21432 ; 21433","2016-01-13T16:59:49.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443329/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443329/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment his Department has carried out on the effects of reductions in universal credit work allowance on workers under the age of 25.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","21430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443330","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>The impact of the work allowance change cannot be considered in isolation – it is part of a broader package of measures announced at the Summer Budget, such as the increase to the personal tax allowance and introduction of the national living wage, which strengthens incentives to find work and better paid jobs.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","21429 ; 21430 ; 21431 ; 21432","2016-01-13T16:59:49.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443330/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443330/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment his Department has carried out on the effects of reductions in the universal credit work allowance on (a) working families and (b) people's ability to take on part-time work.","false","Biography information for Chris Stephens","Glasgow South West","Chris Stephens","21433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443331","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-15","<p>(a i) The number of people employed in DWP offices in Stoke-on-Trent at June 2010, which is the earliest information available, was 744. The current number of people employed as at November 2015, latest information available, is 464.</p><p>(b i) Health and Safety Executive (HSE) has an office in Stoke-on-Trent. The number of people employed at 1 January 2010 was 52. Current number of people employed is 31.</p><p>The North Staffs Remploy factory based at Trentham, Stoke-on-Trent closed on 4 December 2012 and 110 people left the factory.</p><p>(a ii) Detailed workforce planning up to 2020 is not yet available. Although reducing and rationalising the estate could result in relocations, there is no centrally driven relocation target to this effect. Any relocation is done based on the operational needs of the department.</p><br /><p>(b ii) The HSE office in Stoke-on-Trent will relocate on 25 January 2016 and 31 people will move to Crewe from that date.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-15T11:03:12.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443331/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443331/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Department for Work and Pensions: Stoke on Trent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of its non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from Stoke-on-Trent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","21455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443332","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-14","<p>DWP officials have been working with the Ministry of Justice to assess the potential impact of the proposed changes to personal injury legislation on the level of recoupment of social security benefits paid by the compensator to DWP. The early analysis indicates that the vast majority of personal injury victims who claim compensation for whiplash do not claim DWP benefits which are recoverable under the Social Security (Recovery of Benefits) Act 1997. Therefore, if this trend continues, the potential changes to the personal injury legislation will have a minimal impact on the level of recoupment of social security benefits. DWP officials will continue to work with the Ministry of Justice as the proposed changes to personal injury legislation are developed and progressed.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-14T13:11:34.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443332/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443332/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Social Security Benefits: Personal Injury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to proposed changes in personal injury law and procedure announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what assessment he has made of the level of potential reduction in recoupment of social security benefits paid to personal injury victims following such changes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","21498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443333","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-14","<p>Employers have legal responsibility for ensuring that their current and future workforce is not barred from working with children or vulnerable adults. It is reasonable to expect employers to pay for these Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) and Protecting Vulnerable Groups (PVG) checks. DWP recognises there may be exceptional circumstances in which it is appropriate for Jobcentre Plus to reimburse the cost through the Flexible Support Fund if this will ensure a claimant can start a job.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-14T16:43:26.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443333/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443333/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443333/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Vetting: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the extent to which jobseekers required to obtain a Disclosure and Barring Service (DBS) check to take up new work can afford to do so; and if he will estimate the cost of jobcentres providing financial support for people in need of a DBS check.","false","Biography information for Holly Lynch","Halifax","Holly Lynch","21494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443334","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>Universal Credit (UC) Advance Payments of benefit are recovered from the UC award over a period of six months. In exceptional circumstances recovery can be deferred for up to 3 months.</p><br /><p>No interest is charged on advance payments of benefit.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-12T17:31:08.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443334/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443334/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443334/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit: Repayments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 15 December 2015 to Question 20339, what the repayment requirements are for universal credit advance payments; and whether interest is charged on those payments.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443335","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>We do not have the information requested at this level.</p><br /><p>I can confirm that in February 2012, 375,000 letters explaining the State Pension age changes were sent to men and women (across Great Britain and Overseas), with a date of birth in the range 06/10/1954 to 05/04/1955.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-12T10:20:30.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443335/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443335/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","State Retirement Pensions: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many men born in November 1954 resident in Preston parliamentary constituency have been notified of changes in the age at which they will receive the State Pension; and on what date his Department contacted those men with that information.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","21515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443336","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>The overall change in the total cost of Housing Benefit from the introduction of the Local Housing Allowance caps into the Social Rented Sector is available on the GOV.UK website and can be accessed using the following link:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480565/SRAS2015_policy_costings_amended_page_25.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/480565/SRAS2015_policy_costings_amended_page_25.pdf</a> (Page 35).</p><br /><p>However, the Department does not hold in the information required to provide the change in the total cost of Housing Benefit for supported housing.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-11T14:38:56.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443336/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443336/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Local Housing Allowance: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the likely change in the total cost of housing benefit as a result of the introduction of capping of housing benefit for tenants in supported housing at the local rate of local housing allowance in (a) 2018-19, (b) 2019-20 and (c) 2020-21.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443337","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>DWP Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-ministers-hospitality-and-gifts" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dwp-ministers-hospitality-and-gifts</a></p><p>The Department has regular meetings with relevant organisations and will meet with them to discuss how the application of local housing allowance rates to social sector tenants, including those living in supported housing, will work as the policy is developed.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-12T14:23:13.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443337/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443337/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Local Housing Allowance: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what organisations he has met to discuss the introduction of capping of housing benefit for tenants in supported housing at the local rate of local housing allowance.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443338","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-13","<p>Due to its commercial sensitivity, the information is not available.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-13T16:42:59.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443338/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443338/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Work Programme: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the contract payment for each of the principal Work Programme providers is for each six month period or quarter.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","21526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443339","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-14","<p>I have had discussions with Health and Safety Executive (HSE) officials on the range of factors affecting offshore safety. HSE has confirmed that it is placing increasing emphasis upon maintenance standards as part of its interventions at offshore installations. I support this approach.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-14T13:02:57.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443339/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443339/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Offshore Industry: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with the Health and Safety Executive on ensuring reductions in operators' production costs do not adversely affect the safety of offshore workers in the oil and gas industry.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","21548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443340","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>The investigation conducted by the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) into the operability and availability of fire detection systems at the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE) was completed in August 2014.</p><br /><p>The investigation was instigated after AWE reported two events to ONR during February 2014 related to fire alarm and detection system failures, one concerning a facility at the Aldermaston site and the other a facility at the Burghfield site. Investigations of these events by AWE uncovered a configuration issue with a system in a third facility.</p><br /><p>ONR’s investigation identified concerns regarding the competency of the maintainers, the delivery and recording of the maintenance and the configuration of the fire alarm and detection systems with regard to their required safety function.</p><br /><p>ONR subsequently wrote to AWE requesting an improvement programme to address these matters, and has since been monitoring AWE’s progress against a comprehensive improvement programme agreed between ONR and AWE. AWE advised ONR in October 2015 that the improvement programme had been completed. This was confirmed by ONR following an intervention in December 2015.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-12T14:44:19.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443340/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443340/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","AWE: Safety Measures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the investigation conducted by the Office for Nuclear Regulation into the operability and availability of fire detection systems at the Atomic Weapons Establishment has been completed.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443341","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>No notifications of non-compliance with explosives labelling regulations were received from AWE during 2015, and therefore no regulatory action was required.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-12T14:29:56.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443341/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443341/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","AWE: Explosives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether the Health and Safety Executive was notified of any cases of non-compliance with explosives labelling regulations at the Atomic Weapons Establishment during 2015 on which action was subsequently taken to address this situation.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","21557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443342","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>The Government considered retaining the original timetable for increasing the qualifying age for Pension Credit minimum guarantee to 65 by 2020 for a temporary period, in addition to alternative timetabling options for increasing the State Pension age to lessen the impact on women facing the largest increases relative to the original timetable. The transitional arrangements brought forward by the Government capped the maximum delay at 18 months rather than two years, at a cost of £1.1 billion.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-12T14:36:20.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443342/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443342/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his contribution of 20 June 2011, Official Report, column 52, on the Pensions Bill [Lords], that the Government would consider transitional arrangements, what transitional arrangements the Government considered.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443343","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>The information could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-12T16:22:26.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443343/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443343/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 20 November 2015 to Question 16608, how many potential overlapping payments between the Universal Credit Live Service and housing benefit have been identified since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443344","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-12","<p>We will notify all claimants who we expect to be directly affected by the change, offering tailored support depending on the claimant’s circumstances.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-12T17:32:43.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443344/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/443344/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-01-07","Universal Credit: Eligibility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to notify universal credit claimants of the changes to their entitlement taking effect from April 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","21590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442823","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-12","<p>We are strengthening business influence in schools, further education, the skills system, higher education and in giving young people a broad experience of the careers options open to them. Our education reforms are ensuring that young people leave school or college with everything they need to get on and succeed in life. The new Careers and Enterprise Company aims to help schools and colleges in England to prepare young people aged 12 to 18 for the world of work, and increase the level of employer engagement in schools and colleges across England.</p><br /><p>In further education we have given employer-led Local Enterprise Partnerships significant local influence over the skills system. National Colleges are being established by employer-led partnerships to design and deliver specific higher level training, and we are working in direct partnership with employers in reforming technical and professional education to ensure the new system provides the skills most needed for the 21st century economy. In trailblazer apprenticeships, employers develop the standards themselves.</p><br /><p>In higher education, the government fully supports and actively encourages collaboration between universities and business. Partnership is needed to ensure graduate skills and employability meet the needs of business, to maximise the university sector’s capabilities in business-led research and innovation, and to realise the benefits of a strong role for Higher Education Institutions in the development of their local economies.</p><br /> <br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-12T17:55:09.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442823/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442823/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-06","Business: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to ensure greater collaboration between businesses and education to promote skills for potential future careers.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","21179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442824","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-15","<p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>The Government is fighting hard to fix the aspects of our EU membership that cause so much frustration in the United Kingdom - so we get a better deal for our country and secure our future. We are confident that the right agreement can be reached.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-01-15T14:43:10.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442824/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442824/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-06","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to prepare for the outcome of the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","21250"
