ragraph 3.22 of English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, how many apprentices with special educational needs or disabilities have not completed their transport-related apprenticeship placements.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","21245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442828","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-15","<br /><p>Apprenticeships are full time jobs with training. We do not interfere in employers’ recruitment decisions or set specific quotas for the number of apprenticeships to be taken up by people with special educational needs or disabilities.</p><br /><p>All employers must fulfil their duties as set out in the Equality Act 2010 for apprentices as they would for other employees. We believe that the overwhelming majority of young people with special educational needs and disabilities are capable of sustainable, paid employment with the right preparation and support. For many, apprenticeships are the best route into paid employment. To support this, people aged 16 and over can apply for Access to Work funding for adjustments to the workplace. In addition, reasonable adjustments are available for any qualifications within apprenticeships to ensure the apprentice has every opportunity to demonstrate their knowledge and skills.</p><br />","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-15T14:52:27.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442828/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442828/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-06","Transport: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to paragraph 3.22 of English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the planned 30,000 transport-related apprenticeships which will be taken up by apprentices with special educational needs or disabilities.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","21246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442829","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<br /><p>The Five Per Cent Club has been developed and is run by businesses themselves who commit to making a public declaration to achieve five per cent of their company’s overall UK headcount being an apprentice, a sponsored student or on a graduate programme. We do not hold any information on the proportion of planned apprenticeships provided by employers in the Five Per Cent Club which are expected to be taken up by apprentices with special educational needs or disabilities.</p><br /><p>Thousands of disabled people have benefitted from apprenticeships. Of the 499,900 starting an apprenticeship in the 2014/15 academic year, 44,090 of those declared a disability or learning difficulty (LDD).</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-13T17:50:01.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442829/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442829/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-06","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to paragraph 3.28 of English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, what information his Department holds on the proportion of planned apprenticeships provided by the five per cent club which are expected to be taken up by apprentices with special educational needs or disabilities.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","21247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442830","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>The NHS has committed to creating 100,000 apprenticeships by 2020, offering opportunities to thousands of people who wish to pursue a career in the health sector. This is part of a wider, cross-government commitment to reaching three million apprenticeship starts in England across all sectors in 2020.</p><br /><p>Apprenticeships are full time jobs with training. We do not interfere in employers’ recruitment decisions or set specific quotas for the number of apprenticeships to be taken up by people with special educational needs or disabilities. All employers must fulfil their duties as set out in the Equality Act 2010 for apprentices as they would for other employees. We believe that the overwhelming majority of young people with special educational needs or disabilities are capable of sustainable, paid employment with the right preparation and support. For many, apprenticeships are the best route into paid employment. To support this, people aged 16 and over can apply for Access to Work funding for adjustments to the workplace. In addition, reasonable adjustments are available for any qualifications within apprenticeships to ensure the apprentice has every opportunity to demonstrate their knowledge and skills.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-01-13T17:01:07.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442830/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442830/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-06","NHS: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to paragraph 3.22 of English Apprenticeships: Our 2020 Vision, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the planned 17,000 NHS apprenticeship starts which will be taken up by apprentices with special educational needs or disabilities.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","21248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442831","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Government is considering the impact of business rates on all business sectors including energy intensive industries, manufacturing industries and the retail industry as part of the business rates review. The review will be fiscally neutral and will report at Budget 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","21275 ; 21276","2016-01-11T16:55:28.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442831/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442831/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-06","Non-domestic Rates: Energy Intensive Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps in the business rates review to make specific provision for energy intensive industries.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442833","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Government is considering the impact of business rates on all business sectors including energy intensive industries, manufacturing industries and the retail industry as part of the business rates review. The review will be fiscally neutral and will report at Budget 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","21274 ; 21276","2016-01-11T16:55:28.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442833/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442833/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-06","Non-domestic Rates: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps in the business rates review to make specific provision for manufacturing industries.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442834","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-11","<p>The Government is considering the impact of business rates on all business sectors including energy intensive industries, manufacturing industries and the retail industry as part of the business rates review. The review will be fiscally neutral and will report at Budget 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","21274 ; 21275","2016-01-11T16:55:28.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442834/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442834/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-06","Non-domestic Rates: Retail Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will take steps in the business rates review to make specific provision for the retail industry.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","21276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442836","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-03","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has been in discussion with HM Treasury and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills to determine the parameters, principles and feasibility of a tax model. HMRC has also consulted with international organisations to consider best practice in this area. Further meetings are planned following the next round of negotiations when we expect some of the parameters for the model will become clearer.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-03T17:19:12.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442836/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442836/answer",,,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-01-06","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to the letter from Lord Livingston of Parkhead to the Chairman of the European Scrutiny Committee of 3 July 2014, Deposited Paper DEP2015-0877, what progress HM Revenue and Customs has made establishing a cross departmental working group to take forward the modelling of the tax implications of the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","21295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442837","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-14","<p>The Government is committed to tackling alcohol fraud. Alcohol producers have to be licensed or gain approval by HMRC to operate. Illegal production is off-record and often involves the counterfeiting of established alcohol brands; chiefly spirits.</p><br /><p>Detections of illegally produced alcohol in shops are low. However, because of the potentially serious health consequences of consumption, vigilance by enforcement agencies and the public is crucial.</p><br /><p>HMRC responds robustly to all discoveries of illegal production of alcohol and works collaboratively with other enforcement agencies such as Local Authority Trading Standards and the Police, to tackle the sale of counterfeit alcohol. As well as exchanging intelligence, HMRC and Trading Standards Officers take part in joint exercises targeting retailers in specific regions to detect illegal products. Agencies working together can bring a broader range of sanctions and penalties against those who chose to flout the laws.</p><br /><p>Sales of alcohol that are suspected to be illegally produced, counterfeit or untaxed can be reported to HMRC by using hotline number 0800 595 000, which is available 24 hours a day, seven days a week.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-01-14T17:49:26.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442837/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/442837/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-01-06","Alcoholic Drinks: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to tackle the sale of illegally-produced alcohol in shops.","false","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson","21312"
